text.text:
This park is in dire need of renovation. The fountain structure is sad-looking and is falling apart. It could be renovated into a larger stage where the park can earn money by holding live music, art galleries, film festivals, and etc. The grass area needs to be trimmed and changed to an area where people can sit and have picnics or watch the aforementioned entertainment.

While I was here this afternoon, around 2pm, I saw a man run from Emerald to pee behind the fountain. This was all witnessed by the park's security guard, who did nothing to stop it. That's the kind of place this park has become--a public restroom for disgusting people. It could be so much more lucrative if only it were renovated.

text.text:
Washington Sycip was a Chinese-Filipino-American accountant who worked diligently throughout his life to better the community around him. He served with honor in the United States armed forces after learning of his father‚Äôs imprisonment and later in life had great success in accounting, banking, and financing.

I can think of no better way to honor him than to walk under the shade thinking what we can do for one another ‚Äî to be of service.

Compared to Legazpi Active Park this park is far more tranquil with a lot more greenery. The trees are quite lovely, the pond is quaint, plenty of spaces to sit & eat a meal; plus, large enough for a moderate paced walk.

It has a cute vibe where you could bring someone after a meal for a good saunter under the shade. There is some ‚Äúart‚Äù that is pleasant to observe. It gets hot here in Manila but with a place of respite like this it‚Äôs something that can be endured.

text.text:
Marikina Freedom Park is a cherished public space that beautifully captures the essence of freedom and community in Marikina City, Philippines. Having explored this park, I must say that it is a refreshing and vibrant sanctuary that offers respite from the bustling city life.

The park's natural beauty is a highlight, with lush greenery, well-maintained gardens, and scenic pathways. It provides a serene environment for relaxation, exercise, and leisurely walks. The well-placed benches and shaded areas invite visitors to sit back, unwind, and enjoy the peaceful ambiance.

Marikina Freedom Park also serves as a gathering place for the community, hosting various events, festivals, and concerts throughout the year. It is a hub for cultural and recreational activities, fostering a sense of unity and camaraderie among residents. The spacious open area accommodates large crowds, providing ample space for socializing, picnicking, and outdoor games.

Moreover, the park pays homage to the city's rich history and heritage. The presence of monuments, sculptures, and plaques commemorating significant events and personalities adds a layer of cultural significance to the park. It serves as an educational space, allowing visitors to learn and appreciate Marikina's past.

The park's well-maintained facilities, including clean restrooms and convenient parking spaces, contribute to a pleasant visitor experience. The park management ensures cleanliness, safety, and security, making it an inviting destination for individuals and families.

In conclusion, Marikina Freedom Park is a delightful urban oasis that showcases Marikina City's commitment to providing its residents with a beautiful and inclusive public space. Its natural charm, community-centric atmosphere, historical significance, and well-maintained amenities make it an ideal place for recreation, reflection, and celebration. The park exemplifies the city's dedication to creating a vibrant and livable environment for all.

text.text:
Pasig Rainforest Park, or Rainforest Adventure Experience (RAVE), is an adventure park operated and maintained by the Pasig City Government, as evidenced by the official receipt bearing the name of Pasig City.

It is located near the West Bank Road, a steepy road that connects to C6 along Cainta to Bicutan.

It is a combination of amenities, from mini-zoo to swimming pool, a boat ride pavilion, a Butterfly House and flower fields, an amphitheater for public assembly, fitness centre, and some obstacle course with zipline and skate park.

Unfortunately, the adventure park consisting of zipline to skatepark and obstacle is temporarily closed as of 2023.

Generally, the entrance is free for all. If you're going to swimming pool, or visit the mini A-maze, butterfly House, Boat Ride, and Flower fields, there is a separate charge, which is only P10-P50.

Around the year 2012, the zipline was P500 for one zip. Unfortunately, it is closed indefinitely.

There is a mini-zoo, such as monkey and ostrich.

There are gazebos to rest in.

They have refreshments inside the park, from mini-donuts to ice cream.

text.text:
Pasig Rainforest Park is a wonderful destination for nature lovers and families looking for a day of outdoor fun. The park is located in Pasig City, Philippines, and offers a wide range of activities for people of all ages.

One of the main highlights of the park is its vast green spaces and lush vegetation. Walking through the park feels like stepping into a tropical rainforest, with tall trees providing shade and a refreshing breeze. The manicured gardens and well-maintained pathways make it a perfect spot for a leisurely stroll or a picnic with friends and family.

There are also a variety of amenities and facilities available within the park. For those who enjoy physical activities, the park has a large playground area with swings, slides, and climbing structures. There is also a boating lagoon where visitors can rent paddle boats and enjoy a relaxing ride on the water. For fitness enthusiasts, there are fitness stations and jogging paths scattered throughout the park.

One of the standout attractions of Pasig Rainforest Park is the butterfly garden. The garden is home to many species of colorful butterflies, and visitors can get up close and personal with these beautiful creatures. It's a great learning experience for kids and adults alike, as they can observe the different stages of the butterfly life cycle and learn about the importance of conservation.

Overall, Pasig Rainforest Park is a fantastic destination for a day out in nature. The park offers a peaceful and serene environment, with plenty of activities to keep everyone entertained. Whether you're looking for a quiet spot to relax and unwind or a place to have some fun with the family, this park has it all.

text.text: I was still in my teens when I first step and love this parkil in the heart of Makati City. With trees and shrubs abound providing shades and colors and perfectly trimmed bermuda grass to sit and relax when those concrete benches were already occupied. The Pasig River with ferries and fishing boats passing by once in a while in front of the park. While the other side of the river is the City of Mandaluyong where those majestic condominiums stood in contrast with old neighborhood beside. The memories came back but with added provisions like a stage for perfomances and events. There is also the Blue Cavaliers Drum and Bugle Corps practicing every night. Their performing arts and music shows how much the arts culture of Makati is still alive.

text.text:
This is a prime example of delayed gratification. It is so exhausting on the way up, but when you arrive at the top, all of those efforts vanish and all you're left with is awe of the breathtaking view of the NCR and her neighboring provinces.

If you want to get here from Manila via commute, ride a bus that will stop at Tungko. You can be dropped at BDO Tungko, then ask for the locals there where is the jeepney terminal for Licao-Licao. From the terminal, it is almost an hour of trip to the jeepney stop at Licao-Licao. Jeepney fare is P35. Arriving at Licao-Licao, you can ride your way to the Brgy. Balagbag Hall where you will register and be assigned a tour guide. Motor fare is P40 for forth route and P35 for the back route. Tour guide designation is mandatory, for you will not be able to climb up the mountain without it. Cost is P350 for a minimum of 1 and a maximum of 7 people. Halfway through the mountain, there is also a checkpoint for the Balagbag Mountain Proper. Cost is P50.

It is all woth it. I am now beginning to understand why mountaineers love their craft.

text.text: It really is a beginner's mountain. Enjoy the tricycle ride on one part uphill. We went there a week ago and you can only see a handful of hikers. On top you can see the great view of Rizal, Quezon City and Manila's skyline. At night you can witness the city lights from them as well. See if you can spot Ortigas and Manila Bay as well :)

text.text: Those who are new to hiking may opt to climb this mountain. Not only is it close to Manila but the trail here is so easy one will not get lost. There were actually groups of teenagers without guides climbing with us. Plus, it is not too steep and there is actually a rough road that enables vehicles to climb this preferably motorcycles, mountain bikes, and 4x4 cars. Those who also can't wake up early in the morning should also opt for this mountain since the view here in the afternoon is exquisite. Yes, it may be unbearably hot as one climbs it around 1PM but, along the way, there are sari-sari stores who sell snacks and drinks. Do stop by for a refreshingly cold buko juice that's just PHP 10. Most important in climbing it in the afternoon is that the mountain becomes picturesque. There are spots that look like you're in Africa while some are similar to Batanes's grassy lands that look superb during golden hour. Best of all, as you climb down, there is a chance for you to see both the sun and the moon in appearance. The sun in the left horizon and the moon in the right horizon. That was what we were able to experience here. It was a rare sight! Well, that was according to my friend who has already climbed a lot of mountains. En route to the summit, one will get to pass by a barren spot which allegedly became a shooting location for a Philippine historical film. Other reasons to climb this is that there are picnic tables with a good amount of shade and a camp site where one can put up one's tent. Sleeping overnight here will enable one to star gaze and simultaneously see the city lights from a distance.

text.text:
ABSOLUTELY! SEA OF CLOUD IS PERFECTO!
Having an escape with Nature is always a great adventure.
It is time to chill, relax and forget about the bustling city.
Commune with Nature, feel the cold fresh air, enjoy every tweet of the bird and the abundance of green life.
Nature is a place for reconnecting! A blissful place for a peace of mind that you long deserved.
Mt. Hapunang Banoi in Rizal  has a breathtaking view! The mountains and cliffs is truly an adventure.
What a peaceful day indeed!

Enjoy your holidays, make it worthwhile!

text.text: 90% Assault on your way up. Better bring gloves to take care of your palms and hands as you will need it closer to the summit to support yourself when climbing sharp rocks. Jump off is at Wawa Dam. This is my 2nd time hiking this mountain. Best to hike in December to February so it is neither rainy nor humid before summer. There is a junction where you can rest and buy food. Mountain doggos are present and they are very friendly to people, just make sure not to feed them anything toxic and not to litter in the mountain.

text.text: 03 Jul 2022, as part of my trilogy climb. ongoing urbanization in the surrounding areas aside, i'm always happy to do this trek. Unless you're an experienced (or veteran) hiker, please make sure you are well-rested before you do this, use gloves and trail-rated footwear, and bring lots of water. There are stores at the junction, but they might not be open during weekdays. Be mindful of your steps and your pacing, do not hesitate to ask your guide for assistance or to make you a makshift trekking pole, and do not forget to enjoy the view. Hope to see you there.

text.text: Mt. Daraitan is one of the several stunning mountains located in the beautiful province of Rizal boasting all of nature‚Äôs goodness from pristine rivers and waterfalls, dark hollowed caves of century-old formation of stalagmite and stalactite rocks to the picturesque view of the Sierra Madre range.  Also, expect sea of crowds (yes crowds not clouds) when you reach the summit and a 30m-1hr line for you to have a picture in heart peak. But you will enjoy the clear and cold water in tinipak river after your battle. Make sure to bring enough water and trail food with you, though there's a lot of store in trail and in camp site.

text.text: Laguna, together with Batangas and Cavite, is one of the centers for outdoor activities, such as hiking, because of the hidden wealth in the forested areas. Hiking Mt. Romelo and rappelling the Buruwisan falls was an amazing experience because it has rich bio-diversity, both flora and fauna. There is a body of water that flows on its terrain, thus, this mountain has a high concentration of trees and other plants. It can bring a good combination of adventure and relaxation.

text.text: Derived from the phrases "mataas na bundok," Mt. Manabu hides something that is breathtaking in its forest areas. Gorgeous flora and distinct fauna can be found on the terrain that is composed of tall hardwood and fruit bearing trees, coconuts, shrubs and grasses. This type of terrain serves as a paradise of the civet cats that produces an expensive coffee. In addition, its summit has a wide view of the mountain ranges from afar and the nearby villages and has a cool and refreshing breeze.

text.text:
Mt. Pico De Loro is good for beginners. Depending on your speed, you can finish the climb in 2-3 hours. It is easier to climb during summer but more challenging during rainy season. The hardest part is walking on the muds, it is too slippery. It is advisable to wear shoes with spikes.

It has an iconic huge stone standing on its own. They call it monolit and only one person at a time can climb it.  It is better to climb this mountain early in the morning to avoid long lines in monolit. DIY is possible.

There are stores along the way so you will not get hungry. You may bring your own meal but be sure to keep your trash with you.
The view is breathtaking.

text.text:
My Adventure in Mt Maculot is so much fun . at first I thought we're going to Mt Batulao but we goes to Mt Maculot instead.

I'm excited just like the first time i hike at Mt Gulugod Baboy , I'm with the same group . Although at first I felt nervous for I heard tragic stories and confirmed it by searching through goggle about this place . but because I'm an adventurous person I set aside my worries and become excited about so many things I'm going to witness.

We arrived in Batangas late night already so we start trekking about 8pm. We start our silent journey up with manong (our guide) on the lead and I followed. The trail is narrow and small rocks are hindrance for it rolls beneath our shoes everytime I step on it ,  cause my body to sway a little and I had to stop for a while to regain my balance. Sometimes i  open a conversation with manong guide asking him about his life being a guide and he said his job is his only bread and butter, he send his two children to school that's why his job being a guide is very precious to  him , good job manong!  We rest everytime we stumbled a tree or a hut ,  good thing the moon shines in full so we don't need our flash light anymore for the moon shines brightly upon us.  After so many hours of trekking we arrived at the camp site at last !famished . so,  we eat first before we assembled our tent and after a while we rest for the night.

We start our journey towards the Rockies at 6am, manong guide told us before we rest the night to wake up early so we will be able to see the foggy morning view of taal lake. And yes! it's worth the hardship of climbing those risky Rockies .the views from we're I was is awesome i can't believed i witnessed this breathtaking scenery ...i thank's GOD I'm with the this people and in this beautiful place that God created.

text.text:
The entire trail is about 21km long, based on both my pedometer app readings (I say "both" because I have climbed Mt. Marami twice). But it doesn't have that many ascending portions, which makes it a good mountain for beginners.

Its main attraction is the "silyang bato" (loosely translated as "The Throne of Stone") when you get to the summit.

There are also several rivers you will cross while climbing to the top. You can take a dip in them if you want to cool down for a bit.

As a side note, this mountain, just like many others, becomes very difficult to climb when it's the rainy season because everything is so slippery, so it's best to climb it during the summer.

When you descend, you can go to the barangay hall where you registered to take a shower, so changing after the hike is not a problem. And there are many nearby eateries where you can refuel your tummy for the trip back home.

text.text:
News of the phreatic eruption of Taal Volcano yesterday (12 Jan 2020) made me think of the trip to the crater we took 12 years ago (in 2008). From Tagaytay, we rode down to the lakeside and took a boat to the volcano. From the shore, we rode on horseback up to the crater of the volcano within a volcano and the view was just ... breathtaking!
I hope that after the dust settles, Taal Volcano will recover its beauty. I'm optimistic, though -- look at Mt. Pinatubo. Nature has a way of taking care of herself.

text.text:
All kinds of different pretty fish with funny faces! And some other friends as well. :)

As a Serbian, I've never seen most of these on video, much less in-person. I was simply amazed with the beauty of life at every step of the way!

Even though it was fairly crowded, with a lot of kids running around and pressing their faces on the aquariums, I didn't feel like it was overwhelming. I could get a good view of everything without a problem. People were courteous and let each other have some alone time for photos and videos, or just for the viewing enjoyment.

Waiting lines for buying tickets and entering different areas were minimal.

As for non-attraction facilities, there's a food court and food stalls scattered around. There's also a toy shop. Don't worry, these aren't in areas where our water buddies are. ;)

It takes about an hour and a half to two hours to get through the park if you want to take a good look at everything there is to see.

So go, have a nice stroll, absorb the ocean's bounty, and return as a richer person!

text.text:
It was raining hard and flooding in the streets of Ermita so we decided to stop by this  cozy coffee shop UCC Cafe Terrace, nestled in the heart of Robinsons Manila. We made a very good decision because we adore their Nippon Cheesecake Plain paired with Spanish Latte.

Indulge in a symphony of flavors and immerse yourself in a world of culinary delight with the exquisite Nippon Cheesecake‚Äîwhere every forkful unveils a velvety dance of creaminess and a gentle whisper of sweetness. Crafted to perfection, this cheesecake is a sublime tribute to the artistry of Japanese desserts, delivering a slice of cloud-like elegance that dissolves effortlessly on your palate.

For a truly enchanting experience, pair your cheesecake journey with the Spanish Latte‚Äîa robust espresso and velvety steaned milk elevated by a touch 9f Spanish flair. Watch as the coffee artistry comes alive, mingling with velvety steamed milk, creating an inviting dance of flavors. The Spanish Latte is a heartfelt invitation to savor each moment, as you sip and savor the symphony of textures and tastes.

At UCC Cafe Terrace, Robinsons Manila, flavors are more than ingredients‚Äîthey are stories waiting to be shared. Embark on a culinary escapade that blends tradition and innovation, leaving your senses delighted and your memories enriched.

text.text:
After our museum tour at UST, my classmates and I decided to visit a cafe within walking distance of the campus. As we approached the entrance, we noticed the cafe's aesthetics and welcoming atmosphere. We ordered the "Intramuros" (Manager's Choice) pizza and Carbonara Pasta, along with Slush Kiwi, Matcha Latte, and Caramel Macchiato.

The food was good, but when considering the taste and price compared to other cafes, I felt it was a bit on the expensive side. In my opinion, the food's flavor was ordinary and nothing special about it. The drinks we ordered were too sweet, so it's advisable to inquire about sugar levels when ordering.

Additionally, the cafe was a little bit crowded, which I think was because we visited around lunchtime. I also observed that the food was served in plastic containers, which differed from the images on the menu that showed the dishes on plates. It's important to note that bringing outside food to this cafe is not allowed. On the positive side, the staff were friendly and approachable. The cafe is air-conditioned and offers free Wi-Fi and power outlets, making it a suitable place for studying.

formatted_address: 1781, Malate Bayview mansion, 1064 Adriatico St, Malate, Manila 1004, Metro Manila, Philippines

text.text:
Refuge in the late nights‚Äìearly am. ‚òï üåÉ

Where do you go after a very late dinner? Hard to find a Starbucks, CBTL, or other big chains at 1am. Wander around Remedios Circle (now known as Manila Koreatown) and the night's still early.

One of these is this coffee shop. Many options for coffee and cold drinks. Also serves beer and other alcohol. As well as hot meals. There's also various Korean snacks. Many choices here.

Staff are friendly, indoor seats are a quiet retreat from the live and loud streets. Al fresco tables allow you to mingle with the streets.

+ GCash payment
+ Wall electric outlets
+ Nice washroom

name: La Cathedral Cafe
formatted_address: 636 Cabildo St, Intramuros, Manila 1002, Metro Manila, Philippines

text.text:
If you're looking for a coffee shop with a great view, a nice ambiance, and not too crowded, then La Cathedral Cafe is definitely worth checking out! The rooftop setting provides an open view of the city, making it the perfect spot for a relaxing cup of coffee.

The atmosphere is peaceful and inviting, with a comfortable seating area and plenty of natural light. Whether you're looking to catch up with friends or get some work done, the space is spacious and not too crowded, which makes for a pleasant experience.

Of course, the coffee is top-notch as well! The baristas are knowledgeable and passionate about their craft, and the coffee is always brewed to perfection. Whether you prefer a classic latte or a specialty drink, you're sure to find something you love.

Overall, It is a great spot to unwind, relax, and enjoy a cup of coffee with a stunning view. Highly recommended!
.

text.text:
I was not having the best day today so I went to Intramurous to be in a cafe where I can think and enjoy a view. I saw La Cathedral and was curious to see the place. However, I wasn't able to reserve a table beforehand (which I usually do but today I went out in a rush). Fortunately, the staff of La Cathedral were kind and accommodating. They still let us in (walk-ins). I think Sir JJ is worth mentioning as he was really kind and accommodating with me, he gave me a table and got my orders. He also checked up on me and asked me how my experience was. The orders went out quickly which was really nice (the food is really good! Too bad my appetite wasn't in the best mood that day). Adon is also very kind and attentive to my table. My table was on the side and not a lot of waiters can see me, but he's very attentive and kind to check up on me as well for any additional orders or anything that I need help with, including taking pictures. Overall, my experience with La Cathedral has been amazing and I will definitely come back with my friends (as well as recommend this place to all my friends).

I highly recommend that you reserve a table before coming in to get a better table with a view üòä

text.text:
Black Scoop is deserving of a glowing 5 out of 5 stars for my recent visit. This ice cream parlor exceeded expectations with its outstanding flavors and delightful presentation. From classics to inventive creations, the ice cream selection catered to a range of tastes, leaving me spoilt for choice.

The atmosphere was vibrant and inviting, making it a perfect spot for a sweet treat. The staff was not only friendly but also knowledgeable about their offerings, helping me navigate through the tempting array of options.

The quality of the ice cream spoke volumes about the ingredients used and the craftsmanship behind each scoop. The fusion of unique flavors and traditional favorites created a harmonious symphony of tastes.

Furthermore, the portion sizes were generous, ensuring that every bite was a burst of indulgence. The prices were reasonable, especially given the premium quality of the ice cream.

In summary, Black Scoop provided a stellar ice cream experience that combined innovation, flavor, and value. If you're in search of exceptional frozen delights served with a smile, this place certainly delivers.

name: Manila Bay Beach
formatted_address: Roxas Blvd, Malate, Manila 1004, Metro Manila, Philippines

text.text:
Manila Bay Beach is a fascinating destination that beautifully blends natural beauty with urban surroundings. This reclaimed beachfront has undergone a remarkable transformation in recent years, making it a must-visit spot for locals and tourists alike.

One of the most helpful aspects of Manila Bay Beach is its accessibility. Located in the heart of the city, it's easily reachable from various parts of Manila. The newly constructed promenade offers a pleasant walk along the waterfront, allowing visitors to enjoy stunning sunsets and fresh sea breezes.

The cleanliness and maintenance of the beach are commendable. Efforts have been made to keep the shoreline free from trash and debris, creating a more inviting environment for beachgoers. The addition of vibrant beachfront cafes and restaurants enhances the overall experience, offering a variety of culinary delights to savor.

Furthermore, Manila Bay Beach often hosts cultural events and festivities, adding to its charm. Whether you're looking for a peaceful evening stroll, a delicious meal with a view, or a lively event, Manila Bay Beach has something for everyone.

In summary, Manila Bay Beach's accessibility, cleanliness, and vibrant atmosphere make it a highly recommended destination for those seeking relaxation and entertainment in the heart of Manila. It's a wonderful place to unwind and enjoy the beauty of the bay while being surrounded by the energy of the city.

Just a place where you can unwind if you need a breather from the city's noise.

text.text:
I recently had the pleasure of staying at Daluyon Beach and Mountain Resort, and I can't say enough positive things about my experience.

First and foremost, cleanliness is a top priority at Daluyon. The entire property is well maintained, which added to the overall comfort of my stay.

The beach views at Daluyon are nothing short of spectacular. Waking up to the gentle sound of the waves and being able to enjoy a  breathtaking view of the beach and clear waters of the sea had a very therapeutic effect.

What truly sets Daluyon apart, however, is the excellent service provided by their dedicated staff. Administrator Joyce is a true gem, always ready to assist with a warm and welcoming smile.
Restaurant manager Rico and his team deserve a special mention as well. The dining experience at Daluyon was great, with delicious food served in a beautiful setting.
Lastly, I had the pleasure of going on guided tours with Jimmy, one of the resort's tour guides. He was knowledgeable about the local area and was very accommodating and attentive.

In summary, my stay at Daluyon Beach and Mountain Resort was nothing short of amazing. The combination of cleanliness, breathtaking beach views, and the exceptional service provided by the staff make this resort a must-visit destination.

They upgraded us because our original room's AC unit didn't work. Breakfast that came with the room was not buffet but good enough for us. The entire staff was very accommodating and serving, representing the hospitable culture of the Filipinos. We had a total of 12 dives in 4 days. The dive master, Jonah, was great. He doesn't even need weights to dive, which we found quite unbelievable.

After a few meals at the hotel, we decided to walk about 20 min to Sabang town to eat there. It's a bit of walk but pleasant enough, as we were by the water most of the time. The Sabang pier was full of locals and tourists alike, chilling by the water. Overall, very relaxing budget friendly choice.

text.text:
It was an amazing experience. We are surprised they only get 7000 tourists a year but we have no complaints about that since we had the cave to explore only to ourselves.

Instructions:
1. Go to the National Museum to get a permit without charge.
2. Go to the Coastguard and they will find a boatman for you. Charge is Php800 per pax.
3. The boat ride to the cave was about 20 min once you get there, you will need a tourguide. They don't charge but we know that they live on tips so we gave Php400. Fair price.

It is a bit of a hike. We were spelunking for a couple hours. There were monkeys and monitor lizards around. They are currently developing other caves and it will soon be open to the public. We would definitely come back again!

text.text:
Under rated historical spot but a must visit for every Filipino. Maybe the location hampers the tourist to visit this place.
Fortunately, our visit coincided with the high tide so it‚Äôs much easier for the boats to dock. We walked almost 50 meters along the walkway until we reached the entrance of Liyang Cave. We approached the lone caretaker and we paid PhP20 for environmental and maintenance fee. Since some of our companions already went here, they also served as our tour guide.
LIPUUN POINT RESERVATION
The Tabon Cave complex is part of Lipuun Point Reservation, which has the size of 138 hectares and connected to the Palawan mainland via an isthmus and mangrove forest. The National Museum is currently tasked to protect and preserve the reservation. Rich in cultural and natural resources, the area was declared a Site Museum Reservation on April 11, 1972. The reservation is protected by the national government as a museum reservation to protect the caves and immediate vicinity from deforestation and to preserve the cultural artifacts present there.
LIYANG CAVE
The Liyang Cave is the first to go so we wandered around here. It has big chambers and bright lights outside. Cave openings are also visible from the shore. Markers were installed about the stone flakes as well as the flora and fauna in this site including the Palawan hornbill, balinsasayao, tabon bird, binuang tree and extinct deers.
TABON CAVE
As we exited the Liyang Cave we went up the stairs leading to a cave ‚Äì the Tabon Cave. It is said to be the Philippines‚Äô Cradle of Civilization. It is also the largest cave in the entire Lipuun Point Reservation. According to the marker, the chamber is 41 meters long, dry and bathed in sunlight throughout the day. These ideal features explain why the ancient man chose Tabon Cave as a dwelling place for at least 50,000 years ago. The earliest human remains in the Philippines known as Tabon Man was recovered in this cave. The recent study shows that the remains are 47,000 years old. But it‚Äôs a little bit disappointing as the site is littered with cement bags.
TABON BIRD
During our wandering we noticed one bird that is said to be the cave‚Äôs regular visitor, and where the cave‚Äôs name was derived from ‚Äì the Tabon bird or the Philippine scrubfowl. They often stay on the ground but will fly away at a short distance when disturbed. True to its word, it digs out sand, bat droppings or guano, or soil to build their nests, lay its eggs, and cover them. As the eggs hatch, the chicks will come out from the mound. The word Tabon in Filipino means to cover.

SITE RULES AND REGULATIONS
In order to protect and preserve the reservation, all visitors must strictly observe the following:
- No hunting, disturbing and handling of any animal from the reservation.
- The destruction and removal of any plant from the natural habitat are strictly prohibited.
- No littering of any waste.
- The destruction and collection of objects of natural beauty such as corals and limestone are not allowed.
- No vandalism.
- No damaging of trails.
- Artifacts cannot and must not be removed from the caves.
- No altering, removing or defacing boundary marks or signs.
- Animals not native to the reservation may not be introduced at any time.
- No removal and harvesting of forest products.
- No bringing of food and eating along the trail.
Note: The manunggul jar artefact is now under the care of National Museum of Anthropology

name: Siete Pecados

description.text: Popular snorkeling spot featuring coral reefs with diverse species of colorful tropical marine life.

formatted_address: X6MJ+772, Coron, Palawan, Philippines

text.text:
Backpacker on a budget here - Only 300 pp and one of the best snorkelling ever.

Totally worth it! From Coron P.T. take a motorcycle or trike down (east) towards Siete Pecados and turn right onto another little dirt road that goes down into a little town/settlement. Take a slight right and head for the basketball court.

We parked our motorcycle and went to the tourist info center. There you pay 200 pp for either a kayak or a boat and 100 pp for the environmental fee. Our friends rented snorkels for 100. They gave us a discount for 4 people which was very nice. This is the most beautiful island I've ever seen my life! Photos and videos will never give it justice. I will definitely go back!!!

Highlights:
- The water is so clear and blue!
- Turtles swimming around near the shore
- Few meters away there are GIANT clams
- Tons of snorkel sites a few meters away
- Sarap ng seafood!
- Super windy at night, presko! No need for electric fan. Request if you can sleep at the veranda.

- Manual flush for toilets
- Cell service is not good, so it's not a place where you can work remotely. But they do have Starlink Wifi open at night.
- Electricity runs via generator only at a scheduled time at night.

originalText.text: Palawan Island is a stunning and biodiverse island located in the western part of the Philippines

text.text:
Puerto Princesa is a coastal city located on the island of Palawan in the Philippines. It is known for its stunning natural beauty, pristine beaches, and diverse ecological attractions.

One of the main highlights of Puerto Princesa is the Puerto Princesa Subterranean River National Park, a UNESCO World Heritage Site and one of the New7Wonders of Nature. The underground river, also known as the Puerto Princesa Underground River, is a remarkable natural wonder that boasts limestone formations, unique flora and fauna, and a captivating underground river system. Exploring the river on a boat tour is a must-do experience that allows visitors to witness the awe-inspiring beauty of the cave and its surrounding environment.

Apart from the underground river, Puerto Princesa offers a range of other attractions and activities. Honda Bay, located just a short distance from the city center, is a popular destination for island-hopping tours, snorkeling, and swimming in crystal-clear waters. The nearby islands of Snake Island, Pandan Island, and Starfish Island offer picturesque landscapes and vibrant marine life.

Nature enthusiasts will also enjoy a visit to the Palawan Wildlife Rescue and Conservation Center, formerly known as the Crocodile Farm. Here, visitors can observe various species of crocodiles, as well as other wildlife, including endemic birds and reptiles. The center plays a vital role in the conservation and rehabilitation of endangered species.

Puerto Princesa is also renowned for its commitment to sustainable tourism and environmental conservation. The city has implemented several initiatives to protect its natural resources, including the mangrove forests and the Tubbataha Reefs Natural Park, a UNESCO World Heritage Site known for its exceptional marine biodiversity and diving opportunities.

Furthermore, the city offers a range of accommodations, from luxury resorts to budget-friendly guesthouses, along with an array of dining options that showcase local Palawan cuisine.

Overall, Puerto Princesa is a paradise for nature lovers and adventure seekers. Its stunning natural attractions, commitment to environmental conservation, and warm hospitality make it a top destination in the Philippines. Whether you're exploring the underground river, snorkeling in Honda Bay, or simply enjoying the laid-back beach atmosphere, Puerto Princesa offers a memorable and enriching travel experience.

name: Calauit Island National Park

description.text: Island sanctuary since 1976 offering exotic & native wildlife, plus an information center & camping.

formatted_address: 7VHJ+4VC, Busuanga, Palawan, Philippines

text.text:
Getting up close with real live giraffes and zebras was a remarkable experience. These magnificent animals roam freely on the island, giving you a taste of their natural habitat. Plus, the highlight - feeding the gentle giraffes!

While the safari was amazing, I do have a concern about their mini zoo. The crocodiles, civet cat, and Philippine porcupines are housed in rather tiny enclosures. I hope they can work on improving their living spaces for these animals.

It's important to note that getting to Calauit Safari is a bit of a journey, nearly a 2-hour drive from Coron town proper. The surroundings may not be teeming with attractions, but the experience of being so close to these incredible creatures is truly worth the trip!

text.text:
If you're a fan of giraffes and zebras, don't miss the opportunity to visit Calauit Island National Park. The park tour costs 725 PHP per person and a boat ride to the island costs 700 PHP per boat. If it's raining, it's essential to take a ride, as the paths can get slippery and hard to navigate.

Once inside the park, you'll find numerous giraffes and zebras lazily strolling around the grasslands. There's a center where visitors can feed the giraffes. Holding a bunch of leaves, you'll see the giraffes gravitate towards you. It's a moment when you can gently embrace them, or even lean your head against theirs. A visit to this unique place is indeed a worthwhile experience.

name: Kayangan Lake
formatted_address: Swimming Area, Island Hopping - Kayangan Lake, Bayan ng Coron, Palawan, Philippines

text.text:
You don't want to miss visiting Kayangan  Lake when in Coron, Palawan!

Upon arrival, you will be welcomed by the beautiful site of food stalls in the water. After that, there's a little bit of hiking to access the lake. Elderly will have difficulties with this, kinda steep. But the hike will be all worth it.

The stunning turquoise, crystal-clear water was so relaxing. Interestingly, the water is fresh but a little bit salty. Surrounded by greens and the sounds of nature, wear your life jacket and float away.... Relax, enjoy, and live the moment.

text.text: Kayangan Lake is an absolute gem hidden within the breathtaking landscapes of Coron. Having visited this pristine natural wonder, I am left awe-struck by its unparalleled beauty and the ethereal experience it offers to all who venture to explore it. One of the highlights of my visit was climbing up a wooden platform to a vantage point that offered a panoramic view of the lake. The vista was nothing short of breathtaking, with the lake's pristine waters framed by the dramatic limestone cliffs that define the landscape. I found myself lost in the sheer beauty of it all, and I couldn't resist capturing the scene with my camera.

text.text:
Who would've thought theres still an area near batangas where you could swim in  a pristine clear ocean. The water is so clean you could see the sea bed.

The beachfront itself is maintained by Eagle point so there is a 200 php entrance on the area.

Getting there is also quite expensive as you would have to get a boat ride from Mabini to the island itself.

Do not forget to bring your own food as there is no food avaialable in the area. Ihaw ihaw tho is available .You do need bring the food tho.

There's a relatively clean and maintained restroom in the area. And there are tables and chairs you can rent.

The sand is a bit gritty so aqua shoes are recommended.

Overall an enjoyable experience for those who want to snorkel and be away from the city.

text.text:
Calayo Beach cove is a hidden gem deep in Nasugbu, Batangas' mountainous landscape. From Tagaytay it would only take 45 minutes to reach. Coming from Manila via Cavite would take you  two and a half hours. Calayo Beach is also a jump off point for island hopping such as Pulo and Bituin Island.
If you're longing for that serene, calming feeling away from the hustle and bustle of city life... then head now to Calayo.

The place is ok just for relaxation. CR is clean and basic things needed are available at the stores nearby. The beach is not that deep. So for those who wants just to play in the water, this is good. But water got muddied easily because water is shallow. You can have a neck deep water around 500m from the shoreline.
Just beware when you decided to ride in a boat. They will say 1500php for an hour of boating but will not specify that its only for 10 persons. If you exceeded, they will ask you for 150/persons including kids.

We were 19 persons, but they have us squeezed into a single boat then, they asked us for 150 each. But the island where you will visit is very good. Has a clear water and great view

name: Manuel Uy Beach
formatted_address: QJXQ+93C, Calatagan, Batangas, Philippines

text.text:
Beach was nice, they have plenty of staff so the place/resort is clean. Garbage bin was cleared all the time.

2 major let down was you have to pay for cooking  needs, everything is paid individually and at it is a bit of a rip off. You have to rent every single piece of item you need if you plan to go there without bringing anything with you.

2nd was their shower area!!! i swear both my hands went numb coz you have to constantly turning the shower knob to keep the water flowing. Oh and note that the water flow was so slow... you can barely take a proper bath. So I just rinse off the sand with a bit of soap coz it will take me forever to finish. Something they should give a deep thought of for their paying customers.

I would suggest to bring your own stove, cooking utensils, pots and pans, plates and cutleries. They have free use of grilling station, first-come-first serve. Bring your own comfy camping chairs and table coz you have to rent their table and chairs too.

I would also suggest to bring what you need before entering coz stuff inside are pricey from rice, sodas, foods, Ice cubes etc...

text.text: We went here on Aug. 14-16 with my family and relatives. For me, the long drive just to be here is not worth it. Yes, their pools are nice, and the sunset and view are beautiful but the beach water is not good, especially when it rained (it rained every night during our stay), the water in the beach is brown and leafy. There are no nearby outside restaurants so if you didn‚Äôt bring food to cook, you‚Äôll be stuck eating in their restaurants. The food on both their restaurants - Lagoa and Pico Restaurants and Bar is expensive and not worth your money because it doesn‚Äôt taste good. And the service in Lagoa is BAD. Takes too long to prepare food, employees like chitchatting, they don‚Äôt go to your table to get orders unless you call them, and seems like they can‚Äôt handle more than 20 people in their restaurants. The rooms are owned to different people, so it depends on the cleaner of the owner on how clean your rooms will be. My family stayed in Myna A 109, the rooms is clean, it has water in the dispenser, it has refrigerator - the wire shelf in the freezer though was rusty, and the beds‚Äô mattress are thin and cheap I can feel the frame when lying down. And the mattress and pillows are stinky, like they have been wet and were not dried properly. And the water in our bathroom was dirty. It was light brown even after running. I would post a photo of the water but no option to attach a photo in this review. So all in all, it‚Äôs not worth it going here!

text.text: We visited last week from July 11-13, and our overall experience with the facilities was fantastic. The beach was safe, and the pool was clean, with all areas well maintained. However, I must address the food aspect. Unfortunately, the food experience significantly detracted from the otherwise excellent stay. While the prices were high, the quality and value for money did not meet our expectations. The worst incident occurred on our second day when we ordered bulalo and discovered a piece of plastic in it. This was a highly disappointing and unsanitary experience. Food quality and safety should be an area of focus for improvement.

I visited here with my girlfriend and her family. I was expecting a really nice resort based on what they‚Äôve told me. However, the resort itself was very mediocre and very overpriced for the quality, we got an overpriced air bnb for a night which was fine, as the hotel had no rooms left. We got a wristband that you need to keep on which was very frustrating to constantly have a ribbon on your wrist.

The beach was okay bar some patches of rubbish floating around in the sea. The biggest disappointment was the food, the restaurant had some of the worst food and pizza I‚Äôve ever tasted. It took 40 minutes to get it and it‚Äôs basically just a pizza someone threw together and put in an electric oven. If you‚Äôre going to market yourself as a classy resort at least have some decent food available. Let one of your restaurants to a decent franchise if you‚Äôre not going to put in any effort yourself into creating above very sub standard food. I was delighted to finally be leaving after spending a day there.

Also very classless to have review botting for your ratings. Improve your resort and maybe you will not need to artificially increase your rating score. Those profiles are clearly fake if you look at them and all come within the same hour of each other posting.

text.text:
The beach itself is fair enough, with the nice sand and clear water. The waves were strong during our visit, but it was nevertheless enjoyable to swim in. Here are a few things to mind though:
‚Ä¢ Limited seating/beach chairs especially for how busy it gets during peak times
‚Ä¢ Sometimes there may be an increased presence of marine life such as jellyfish or sea urchins. While there are efforts in removing them, still do be advised.

As for the bar, the price of the food is higher than usual, but that's expected considering it's catered towards hotel guests staying and tourists.

There are a few things I hope they can improve on, however, such as:
‚Ä¢ The water pressure of the shower areas
‚Ä¢ Replacement/overhaul of broken facilities especially the faucets of said shower areas
‚Ä¢ Better clean up of both the beach area and the surrounding water. From time to time, garbage can be seen
‚Ä¢ Presence of more life guards

name: Sabangan Beach Resort

description.text: Low-key quarters, some beachfront, in a casual resort offering an outdoor pool & free meals.

formatted_address: Valle Verde, Pasig, Batangas, Philippines

text.text:
Went here for a weekend getaway.

Beach is well-maintained and clean, as well as the pool. We enjoyed sitting by the beach even after sunset. The overall vibe of the resort is cozy and relaxing.

In the booking confirmation, it is mentioned that there's a managed buffet, but their staff is not accommodating. Some of them are giving guests "the look" when they decide to have another round or get refills. The food is okay.

We stayed in their Bamboo room. I was not able to sleep peacefully because a rat was running around our room. The rat can probably enter the room because of the hole near the aircon. When I mentioned it upon checkout, the staff just told me that they would report it and didn't apologize. Also, there are clear windows beside the shower of the restroom, and it feels uncomfortable when taking a bath.

Overall, we will still recommend the place, but please make sure to review the details of the room you're booking to ensure a relaxing stay and avoid the Bamboo one.

text.text: The resort is incredibly accommodating to seniors and pet-friendly, which made our experience all the more enjoyable. We opted for the day tour option and were pleased to find that the resort had designated rooms for day tour guests. The food was absolutely delicious and the beach was simply stunning. I also took advantage of the massage services and found them to be incredibly relaxing. One small area for improvement would be the organization of the resort and rooms are kind of old and the availability of additional activities for guests. However, this did not detract from our overall enjoyment and we would definitely recommend Sabangan Beach Resort to others looking for a fun and relaxing day trip destination.

text.text:
Great resort though needs some renovation as it is one of the older establishments but one of the more spacious resorts. The place is not cramped, unlike the newer resorts. You have a real pathway where you can walk, enjoy the stroll from your room to the beach, and breath.

Homey hotel. They serve afternoon snacks, dinner, and breakfast as scheduled. Guests actually eat together and eat the same meal because of the buffet. Thus, for the family since after dinner, you have time to cool down and enjoy the silent night and buzz of nature.

Not for the energetic or younger ones because they don't offer any sort of entertainment after dinner while resorts are still noisy because because of some event or party.

The room is just right to sleep in but they have no cabinets for your clothes when you unpack. Would have been better if they have cabinets so you can unpack.

The pool is adequate but needs maintenance as guests frequent it every day.

name: Munting Buhangin Beach Camp
formatted_address: Nash thus 4231, Nasugbu, Batangas, Philippines

text.text: My kids enjoyed the beach and the sand! No tiny pebbles even if you're already far from the seashore. It's safe to swim because your feet can still touch the sand even if you're far from the shore and the waves are not that big. They offer activities such as banana boat ride, jetski and the fisherman from a boat will sell you freshly caught fishes, shells and lobsters! They also allow bon fire at the shore. If you're at the beach camp don't expect too much. The way going there is steep and rough road. Don't bring a lowered car and going there at night is not recommended. When you arrived at the destination, you have to go down a staircase with more or less than 30 to 50 steps. The kuyas and the security guard are helpful in assisting you to bring your stuff going down to your designated villas. Some villas are already old and dilapidated. But the villa we stayed in is still good. The cooking appliances and utensils are complete some of them still have a tag price. During our stay, the electricity was cut twice but only for a brief second. We ran out of water supply on our third day but after we reported it, the water flow was back. If you're bringing your kids make sure you have something to put or apply on them to prevent mosquito bites because there are a lot of them. Overall, I enjoyed the beach and sand it's not white but powdery with no pebbles it's way better than galera and will give it 4 stars. Room and service is 2.75 to 3. Location is 2.

text.text: This was a weekend getaway for us. We were a total of 7 people. The facility is situated atop a hill and can be a hassle getting to. Once you get there its an okay place to be. You will definitely feel very close to nature. The accommodation is okay, considering the location but definitely could have been better. The toilet cum bathroom was okay with running water at all times. The free breakfast provided in the morning was okay too. The room we booked was good for 4 people but they allow up to 10 people to sleep there. Extra bedding is available on request and additional charges. The beach itself was not so impressive. We did take a dip in the ocean but I have seen and been to much better beaches. Also, because of the weekend, it was very crowded. I would not prefer going back.

Indoor pool was closed and outdoor pool was too cold to enjoy.
Part of the hotel was closed and we were told that's where they usually have more restaurants/ food options.
The hotel is much smaller than what it looks like on the outside. What you actually get to walk around and see isn't so big.
We wouldn't return, it's not our style or vibes, we were only staying here for a family event that took place in the hotel.

text.text:
I recently had the opportunity to stay at Seda Vertis North Hotel during my visit to Quezon City, and overall, it was a pleasant experience.

The location of the hotel is excellent, situated in the heart of the bustling Vertis North complex, offering easy access to shopping, dining, and entertainment options. The modern and stylish lobby immediately impressed me upon arrival, and the check-in process was efficient and friendly.

The room I stayed in was spacious and well-maintained, featuring contemporary decor and comfortable furnishings. The bed was particularly comfortable, ensuring a good night's sleep. The in-room amenities, including a flat-screen TV and a well-stocked mini-bar, were appreciated.

The hotel's dining options were diverse, and I enjoyed several meals at their restaurant. The food quality was commendable, and the staff provided excellent service.

One area where Seda Vertis North Hotel could improve is in-house recreational facilities. Although they have a pool and a gym, these areas felt a bit limited in size.

Nonetheless, the staff throughout my stay were attentive and courteous, always willing to assist with any requests or inquiries.

In summary, Seda Vertis North Hotel is a great choice for travelers looking for a comfortable and stylish stay in Quezon City, with convenient access to the vibrant Vertis North district. While there are some areas for improvement, my stay was enjoyable, and I would consider returning on my next visit to the area.

name: California Garden Resort
formatted_address: 245 Katipunan Ave, Novaliches, Quezon City, Metro Manila, Philippines

text.text:
We are here lastnight January 30,2018  with my friends and family in total of 12 person  for overnight swimming.We arrive around 1030pm.They charge 250php adult and 200php kids per head for the cut-off of 6pm-6am.
The caretaker/cashier of this place is not approachable  and not accomodating when you are asking for assistance,giving us attitude,smoking ciggarette in front of us.
He was very rude when he approach us asking for payments for my 4 friends that just arrived at 130am,They are asking for the same rate payment regardless that they only have 4 hours left  to use the  said resort.
We ask the caretaker/cashier if he can give us a discount and consideration for my 4 friends that just catch-up to join us.I even ask him to call his boss and tell her about the situation.He was so rude and ask us to go with him in the office.We went to the office with the caretaker/cashier,he call his boss 'Mary Ann',We can see him through the window and he was talking too long,he then finally invite  us to come inside the office to
talk to his boss.Mary Ann the owner,was on the line and was very rude saying that, Why we dont want to pay? I explain to her that,We are just asking for a price adjustment for my 4 friends and they are willing to make a payment.She was very
'rude' and telling me  to make a payment right-now and they don't do a price adjustment,regardless of you just came late,or will just sit down or will not use the ammenities,it's not their problem!They will have to pay the regular rate.She was litterally shouting at me!
I just keep my cool and will not let her ruin our night,I even tell her that she don't have to be rude,shouting at me and this is how they treat their customers?We are just asking if she can give us  a consideration, discount/price adjusment for my 4 friends.She can just say No politely with manners and acted proffesionally.

On behalf of me, my friends and family,We are not recomending this resort.We don't want you to experience what we had.
The resort was also dirty,stinky 'Urine smell' floating in the air,,They have a lot of stray Cats that eats all our food and will attack you of you try to push them away.
Shout-out to 'Mary Ann ',and her employee to your future customers and my fellow Filipino man.
They are Greedy, No Consideration
Poor Customer Service, No Moral Values, and very Unproffesional.They only care about  your Money!
Please enroll your self to have a Moral and to be Educated as an owner and businesswoman so that you can  also teach your employee's to give the right treatment,respect and the proper attitude to your customers.
You will Reap what you Sow..

text.text: The location is very accessible and the price is cheap. However, the facilities are very crusty lol. This is the second time I've stayed here and the room I got was very dirty. I've attached pictures of the wall. It smells moldy and musty like an abandoned house. Everything was dirty. The bathroom looks like it hasn't seen a scrub in forever. There were hairs on the bed. The windows with water stains. It looks like they don't even bother cleaning the rooms after a guest has left. I didn't bother changing hotels because I had an important event to go to and I can't even cancel my booking anymore. The hallways and elevators smell like a really really old, wet book (and not in a good way). There were flies everywhere, including the lobby where the buffet was set. I can't even imagine what the kitchen looks like. ü§¢ Now, it's been three days after I left and I'm still suffering from rashes due to the nasty beddings. I think it had bedbugs. I have been to other hotels and cheap stays with the same price range and I can tell you that this has been the worst experience ever. If this is the only hotel within your budget, I'm really sorry in advance.

text.text: Had to travel to Manila to complete a step in the dual citizenship process. The Bayleaf Hotel is in a perfect location if you need to visit the bureau of Immigration in Manila. Beyond the location being ideal the hotel is by far the nicest one I have stayed in while in the Philippines. Its not close to the airport so might not work as well if you only are spending one night during a layover. If you are planning to spend a few days in Manila, highly recommend giving it a try. The breakfast buffet in the morning was very satisfying and all of the different food and beverages options were top notch. We also dined in the restaurant on the penthouse level for lunch. The food was tasty and service outstanding. If I have to visit Manila again in the future I will definitely be booking a stay at the Bayleaf.

text.text:
Stayed here for 2 nights for a wedding of a friend.

Check in - security personnel were very polite in assisting us from drop off to the parking space even reserve the parking slot when we advise that we are staying for 2 nights and we are worried if we can still have a slot if we go out to go to the church and come back for the reception since the frontdesk advise that it is a first come first serve basis in the parking.

Location -  the hotel is near the gate of intramuros and it is easy to take a tour go to other places which is very accessible even if you take a public transport

Staff - upon check in we ask for an assistance to carry our luggage but the staff who assist us just bump our bags in the wall in the cabinet and we end up helping him out instead. It is hard to call the housekeeping for assistance. We even called 2-3 follow ups to the frontdesk before someone send our request. You should have a very long patience and waiting time before you get served. The staff will not attend you immediately especially when you are a local tourist. You can feel the isolation of foreigner and local from the staff in the frontdesk to the staff in the penthouse. They are also letting the intern assist the guest without proper supervision and giving an incorrect information to the guests and the managers were not even apologetic with their mistakes. Lastly the frontdesk even ask the guard for other checkout and parking policy which is not appropriate. A frontdesk staff should know better than other staffs because they are one welcoming and the first and last touch of the guests.

Food - Complimentary breakfast buffet is not ok. The egg is not fresh, full of fried and process food, less selections, nuggets, chicken longganisa and everyday arroz caldo serving which is very bland. Coffee is a bit acidic, hot choco taste like ovaltine with milk and not a real tsokolate as expected. Fruits were dry and sweet ham is a bit chewy taste like it was thawed from the freezer for couple of days.

Room - 1st night the beddings were a bit itchy, the towels were a bit grayish, we ask for a slippers but the frontdesk advise that it is not included in the accomodation and you need to pay for extra 35 pesos each person to have one. First time to hear that in a hotel accomodation. No laundry bag and they only give us a trash bag since their supplies for the laundry bag is not available. The light is quite din in the nights time no center white light for the night. We requested for a city view but we end up a view beside the LPU roofdeck. We also need to request for our toiletries. On the 2nd day they did not refill the hand towels.

Overall our stay is not worth it for money even for the experience and surely we will never come back. This is one of the overated hotels posted online

text.text:
Disappointing Experience at Azure Urban Resort Residences Room 1711 in Positano.

Last week, my group and I booked two 1BR rooms (RM 1709 and 1711) at Azure Urban Resort Residences in Positano. Unfortunately, our stay was marred by the rude and unprofessional behavior of the part owners of Room 1711.

Shortly after we checked out, we received a call around 2-3 in the morning from Ivan, one of the part owners, regarding the used beddings. According to him, we were not supposed to use the clean beddings reserved for the next guests. However, upon check-in, Ms. Janel Esperanza, another part owner, explicitly informed us that we could use the items inside the cabinet, including those in the rattan basket.

The beddings in our room were filthy, so we decided to change them. Unfortunately, there were no available beddings inside the cabinet, only in the rattan basket. We used the beddings from the basket, unaware that they were intended for the next guests. If we had known, we would not have used them. It is common sense to assume that we should replace dirty beddings, right?

To make matters worse, during my conversation with Ivan, another part owner in the background started shouting and rudely interrupted us. This person even had the audacity to point at me and insinuate that I needed to be shouted at. Is this how professionals handle situations with their guests? I think not.

While we understood that the accommodation was affordable, we did not expect to be treated with such disrespect and unprofessionalism. The behavior of the part owners, especially towards their guests, was completely unacceptable.

In conclusion, our experience at Azure Urban Resort Residences was disappointing due to the rude and unprofessional conduct of the part owners of Room 1711. We hope that the management takes appropriate action to prevent such incidents from happening to future guests.

name: Hotel H2O

description.text: Sophisticated rooms & suites, some with aquariums, plus a restaurant, a spa & a bar with bay views.

formatted_address: Behind the Quirino Grandstand, Manila Ocean Park, Rizal Park, Ermita, Manila 1000, Metro Manila, Philippines

text.text:
This was our fourth visit to this hotel. We have always been more than happy with the hotel and the level of customer service. This trip was definitely different!
It started with them losing our reservation. The next day, the front desk called our room at 7PM and asked if we were extending our stay (our initial reservation was for four nights). We told them that we had booked four nights but now wanted to leave after three.
The buffet, which was an additional fee, used to be huge with the ability to get omelettes custom-made. This trip was four hot dishes with two kinds of fruit and veggies. If the breakfast had been free, I wouldn‚Äôt complain, but for the amount that was charged, I was beyond disappointed.
The staff used to be very pleasant and would always greet us when we walked through the lobby. This time, we were rarely greeted.
The air conditioning was rarely on in the common areas (or if it was, was barely noticeable).
The room was still great, however, there was very little hot water for our showers.
This used to be a four to five star hotel but now I would class it as a two to three star.

This was our fourth visit to this hotel. We have always been more than happy with the hotel and the level of customer service. This trip was definitely different!
It started with them losing our reservation. The next day, the front desk called our room at 7PM and asked if we were extending our stay (our initial reservation was for four nights). We told them that we had booked four nights but now wanted to leave after three.
The buffet, which was an additional fee, used to be huge with the ability to get omelettes custom-made. This trip was four hot dishes with two kinds of fruit and veggies. If the breakfast had been free, I wouldn‚Äôt complain, but for the amount that was charged, I was beyond disappointed.
The staff used to be very pleasant and would always greet us when we walked through the lobby. This time, we were rarely greeted.
The air conditioning was rarely on in the common areas (or if it was, was barely noticeable).
The room was still great, however, there was very little hot water for our showers.
This used to be a four to five star hotel but now I would class it as a two to three star.
The only redeeming quality was the location in Luneta. Unfortunately we will not be returning.

text.text:
Winford Manila is our go-to hotel and the hotel we‚Äôve visited the most in the last couple of years. There‚Äôs just a lot of things to like about the hotel.

The location is great. It‚Äôs right in front of SM City San Lazaro so it‚Äôs easy to just cross the road over to the mall if you need anything or if you want to go for a quick food run. Speaking of food, the hotel breakfast is one of our favorites. They have a good selection of food that‚Äôs actually delicious. Room service was also pleasantly reasonably priced. Other hotels have annoyingly high prices for room service but here it‚Äôs quite reasonable. You still have an option to get something delivered through Grab or go to SM to eat if you want to eat cheaper.

Speaking of cheaper, make sure to check their Facebook page for promotions. They usually have big discounts on rooms so make sure to check before booking. The rooms are priced well to begin with so even if you don‚Äôt get a discount, you‚Äôre still getting a bang for your buck.

The staff are generally attentive, helpful, and friendly. They‚Äôre also very accommodating if you need anything. Security guards probably need a bit of training, I‚Äôd have to say. But they‚Äôre not bad. Just not as overly friendly as other hotel staff.

What we like the most is probably the heated pool. I‚Äôd like to emphasize this one, they have a heated pool! Imagine going for a nice relaxing swim at night. This is something you should try if you haven‚Äôt experienced it already. And the pool is not hot, it‚Äôs relaxingly warm. Makes me want to go back just thinking about it. One more thing, the pool is intelligently designed where there's a shallow area at the side of the pool so adults can still enjoy swimming even when they're looking after their kids. It's just brilliant!

By the way, if you‚Äôre concerned about the casino and you‚Äôre planning to stay with children, don‚Äôt worry. The casino area is totally separate from the hotel. You won‚Äôt even know there‚Äôs a casino unless you look for it. And even if you do find it, your kids won‚Äôt be able to enter anyway.

Overall, we highly recommend the Winford Manila hotel to anyone who is looking for a comfortable, convenient, and affordable place to stay in Manila. The service is excellent, the food is tasty, the facilities are superb, and the location is ideal. It is definitely one of the best hotels in Manila.

You should also ask an ID from guests who have not checked in.

After humiliating me at the front desk for their mistake, they waived my deposit, but the damage was done.

text.text:
‚ÄúA Lot of Tiny Critters (Cockroaches)‚Äù

I‚Äôve killed about 4 of various sizes. And tried to shoo another 5. The Selah Gardens in Pasay/Taft is better. I had high expectations because of my good experience in your other hotel, but this loft type? Nope. Totally opposite. Imagine critters running above your head because the space is so tiny as it‚Äôs a loft style. The price is budget friendly, but the added anxiety is not worth it! Go book someplace else with good reviews. My bad I was enticed with the price and the former good reputation of Selah Gardens that I did not bother to check google reviews. It only had a 3.7 stars!

Oh, plus the receptionists are very inconsiderate on check in time. I arrived at a little over 12 noon and sat by the lobby. When I confirmed from Will if the check in is 2pm, his lady buddy at the reception angrily blurted that it‚Äôs 3PM! Wow. I was not even talking to her and she just unabashedly and rudely interrupted. Fortunately (if you can consider that fortunate), check in was not 3PM. Worst is they will literally let you check in at exactly 2PM and will not consider an earlier check in at least 1:30pm perhaps? Especially for guests who have been waiting at the lobby for 2 hours already! But no! They have no sense of customer consideration at all! In other hotels that I've been to, although their check in time is 2PM, they will be considerate with waiting customers at the lobby and will let me check in earlier (some at 1PM even!).

text.text: The hotel has so much potential (hotel lobby aesthetics was great) however the internet in the room was not working, water damage is visible on the wall paint, electric sockets are very difficult to use (had to ask for the hotel electrician to help us plug our chargers). There were a lot of facilities that were not working or under renovation (the big pool was not used, some of the lockers seem to be not working, the sauna was under renovation). Hotel staff was pleasant however when we went to the floor to inquire about massage or use the lap pool or steam room there was no staff around to help. No coordination amongst the facility personnel, we had to go up the 9th floor to ask from hotel staff and then went went down again the 6th floor only to be told that payment has to be done on the ground floor and then we went up again as the staff who helped us saw someone who can help with the transaction. Overall it was a poor experience, overpriced in my opinion.

text.text:
The hotel lobby is impressive. Gives a museum vibe that celebrates Filipino artistry with bricks, wood, and huge mosaic murals that anyone would appreciate.
Upside: got our rooms on sale so we really got the best bang for our buck. This gave us access to facilities such as the fitness center, water spa, playground, and comes with free breakfast at VS Caf√©. Parking available for guests. Hotel staff are courteous and helpful.
Downside: corridors/rooms looks unfinished, very industrial look and feel. Bathroom doors don't have frosting so this gave all of us zero privacy. On our second stay, we taped some Manila paper over the bathroom door so we can at least do some numbers without anyone seeing.
Do we recommend this place? Yes, especially on promotion.
Are we going back? Maybe yes.

name: Camelot Hotel

description.text: Casual quarters in a castle-themed lodging offering 5 restaurants, 1 open 24 hours.

formatted_address: 35 Mother Ignacia Ave, Diliman, Quezon City, Metro Manila, Philippines

text.text: The hotel, as its name suggests, is themed from a fictional place named Camelot. Its eye-catching external architecture is castle-inspired located in a bustling city where high-rise buildings and modern structures are common. Inside, the hotel is even more inspired by medieval times from its flooring, walls, to furnitures and decors. It has a restaurant and bar at the lobby and function halls. The room is quite a downgrade from its elaborate lobby design, and most furniture and cabinets are old and unusable. A/C needs reconditioning.

text.text:
This place manages to make the medieval theme bearable with the Filipino preferences. The rooms were nice. Fully air-conditioned the moment you go in. So many storage spaces. And clean sheets as you check in. However, the TV was not working while the refrigerator was making strange noises every now and then due to its old age. There are some surfaces that needed cleaning especially in hallways.

I wouldn't consider the service to be "friendly". It felt like we were not welcome and should immediately leave as soon as we check out. A smile won't cost much but improves the overall experience.

The main charm of this hotel is its location. Walking distance to so many restaurants and public transport. A cheap grab drive away from major tourist spots and a tricycle plus metro ride away from 2 major malls. Overall, the experience was nice, dealing the reception is the last thing I wanted from this hotel.

text.text: A budget hotel that will serve just to sleep and take a bath, then that's it. It is spacious enough I think it can fit up to 6 people. They will require you to give 1k security deposit and fyi, they have complete toiletries for 2 but if you requested for extra items like towels, shampoo, or cup of coffee, they have charges for that. My main issue is that the walls are too thin that you can hear the talking and playing of children. Some neighbors are not considerate to be quiet in day and night so, it's important they implement hotel policies to avoid irresponsible guests. Overall, the place is clean, comfy and safe. The location is very near to big malls, churches, and QC circle.

name: Conrad Manila

description.text: Chic rooms & suites in a polished lodging offering bay views, dining & an infinity pool, plus a spa.

formatted_address: Seaside Boulevard, Coral Way, Pasay 1300, Metro Manila, Philippines

text.text:
We had an excellent stay at Conrad Manila. Service was top notch all the way from baggage handling, reception, room service, housekeeping and so on. Everyone was genuinely friendly and helpful. Views were amazing and not to mention it's right next door to Mall of Asia. We stayed here for my partner's birthday and they handled the birthday preparation to perfection. Thanks team for organising our stay, cake and flowers! I highly recommend this place and will definitely be staying here again next time we are in Manila.

Special shout-out to housekeeping for making our room feel so extra clean and tidy! Loved your notes too!

text.text: Stayed in this property for two days and all I can say is wow! Everything is perfect. Our room was upgraded to a bay facing view and in the afternoon its a must to see the sunset. The hotel is very clean, luxurious, the breakfast was great with a wide selection, staff are very courteous, helpful, always willing to lend an extra hand, they always a big genuine smile on their face. You dont have to ask them anything they can anticipate your needs. Remarkable! You can see how they love their job and take great pride in it. From the security, the attendants, life guards, the front desk and the concierge are among the best in the world and I have visited a few Conrad/Hilton overseas. Our stay truly left an impact on me. So thank you!

The rooms were spacious and beautifully designed, offering stunning views of Manila Bay. The attention to detail in the room's decor and amenities was impressive, making my stay comfortable and luxurious.

What truly set Conrad Manila apart was the service. The staff went above and beyond to ensure my needs were met. They were always ready to assist with any request, and their professionalism and friendliness were remarkable.

The location of the hotel is also convenient, with easy access to nearby attractions and shopping areas.

In summary, Conrad Manila exceeded my expectations in every way. I highly recommend this hotel for both business and leisure travelers. It's a place where you can relax in style, enjoy impeccable service, and create lasting memories...

name: New World Makati Hotel

description.text: Modern rooms & suites with free WiFi, plus 2 restaurants, an outdoor pool & a fitness center.

formatted_address: corner Makati Avenue, Ayala Center, Esperanza St, Makati 1228, Metro Manila, Philippines

text.text:
The staff in the hotel are very professional and well-trained. They are very courteous and offer excellent service. Breakfast is a good selection and they can offer very fast service in the morning if you are in a rush. The lobby and lounge area is very nice, good place to rest or meet a friend for a chat. Bar service is great, although if you ordered food you would have to wait quite long. Lounge is packed most nights and the live singers are very good. Location of hotel is very convenient, close by to malls, shops and restaurants.
Only complaint is that the room was very humid when I arrived, to the point where the sheets felt  damp when I went to sleep. Think it was because the room was left vacant for a while so the air-conditioning was barely running. It was much better by the second night.

text.text:
I attended a wedding reception here. I did not like the faucets in the CR as it was so hard to let the water flow out steadily. The water flow just kept stopping. The faucet censors were badly calibrated I believe.

I also disliked the fact that guests had to go out of the hotel in order to go to theirs cars in the parking lot. In other hotels, one does not have to out of the hotel in order to go to the parking lot.

I was really impressed though with the main door greeter. She was mute. I thought how kind the owners/managers of this hotel were to hire disabled people. Wish more hotels would follow the noble example of this hotel.
