text.text:
I booked this room because I needed a place to stay for the night. I chose this hotel over other nearby options because I thought it was cheaper. But after staying there, I realized that there are even cheaper places with better service and amenities.

I was so tired since I just came from a 5-hour drive and it was already past midnight.

Then this happened:

I was stuck in the elevator for a few minutes after it went dead. I was going back to the basement parking to get my phone from the car when suddenly the elevator stopped and the lights went off. The "security" who was with me was more of a bell boy than a security staff, she didn't even know what to do when an elevator went dead. I had to tell her to turn on her phone's flashlight and look for the emergency button. I was starting to panic wondering how long would it take for us to get out of the elevator. I'd never want to go through that kind of experience anymore.

First of all, the mall's design is impressive. It's sleek, modern, and exudes a sense of luxury that is sure to make any shopper feel like a VIP. The mall is spacious and well-lit, which makes for a comfortable shopping experience.

The stores at Newport Mall are top-notch. You'll find a wide selection of high-end brands, from designer clothing to luxurious accessories. The boutiques are tastefully decorated, and the sales staff are knowledgeable and courteous.

Foodies will love the variety of restaurants and cafes available at Newport Mall. Whether you're in the mood for a quick snack or a full meal, there's something for everyone. The food court offers a wide variety of options, including local and international cuisine. You'll also find trendy cafes and upscale restaurants throughout the mall.

text.text:
Decent place on the corner of Hemady and E. Rodriguez. There are many establishments here, such as banks, a Starbucks, Koomi, and an Anytime Fitness on the fourth floor.

The reason I am giving it 3 stars is purely because of the incredibly tight basement parking. The ramp entering the basement parking, as well as the ramp connecting basements 1 and 2, are extremely narrow and tight, on top of being steep. Not only that, the vehicles going up or down use the exact same space. So for those who are inattentive (not that I defend such, it can just happen at times), you may end up in a bit of a situation if you go up or down the ramp the same time as a car going the opposite direction. Perhaps the worst part of it is the turn-in of the ramp from basement 1 to basement 2. For those who drive larger and wider vehicles like I do, it can be a nightmare to get through that part each time without unnecessarily scraping the sides of your car. In my case, unless I have all the room to maneuver in that area in some instances, I would just barely make it through and have the right rear wheel go up the yellow floor divider that ramps usually have. I read an older review here and I would have to totally agree. Hopefully they can manage to widen that particular part of the parking, because it has been a problem for many who have been there prior, as clearly shown by all the scratch marks seen on the walls.The fact that it is free (from my experience) only slightly offsets the tightness of their basement ramps (especially that horrendous turn-in from basement 1 to 2, I cannot emphasize this enough).

The reason I am giving it 3 stars is purely because of the incredibly tight basement parking. The ramp entering the basement parking, as well as the ramp connecting basements 1 and 2, are extremely narrow and tight, on top of being steep. Not only that, the vehicles going up or down use the exact same space. So for those who are inattentive (not that I defend such, it can just happen at times), you may end up in a bit of a situation if you go up or down the ramp the same time as a car going the opposite direction. Perhaps the worst part of it is the turn-in of the ramp from basement 1 to basement 2. For those who drive larger and wider vehicles like I do, it can be a nightmare to get through that part each time without unnecessarily scraping the sides of your car. In my case, unless I have all the room to maneuver in that area in some instances, I would just barely make it through and have the right rear wheel go up the yellow floor divider that ramps usually have. I read an older review here and I would have to totally agree. Hopefully they can manage to widen that particular part of the parking, because it has been a problem for many who have been there prior, as clearly shown by all the scratch marks seen on the walls.The fact that it is free (from my experience) only slightly offsets the tightness of their basement ramps (especially that horrendous turn-in from basement 1 to 2, I cannot emphasize this enough).

Ayala The 30th Mall offers a remarkable and truly special shopping experience, akin to a christening celebration. The mall exudes an air of elegance and sophistication, making it an ideal destination for those seeking a more upscale shopping and dining experience. The ambiance is inviting, with beautifully designed spaces that provide a sense of exclusivity.

The mall features a curated selection of high-end boutiques, making it a haven for fashion enthusiasts. From luxury brands to chic, unique stores, there's something for everyone. The dining options are equally impressive, with gourmet restaurants and cafes offering exquisite dishes and beverages.

What truly sets Ayala The 30th Mall apart is its commitment to creating a memorable atmosphere. The attention to detail in their seasonal decorations and lighting brings a delightful charm to the holiday season, creating an ideal destination for experiencing the joy of Christmas.

Overall, Ayala The 30th Mall is more than just a shopping center; it's a destination for those who appreciate the finer things in life. name: Megamall
formatted_address: M2GV+CF8, Quezon City, Metro Manila, Philippines

text.text:
"Megamall" continues to be a premier shopping destination that never fails to impress. With its expansive size and extensive selection of stores and attractions, it's a shopper's paradise.

First and foremost, the sheer variety of shops and brands at Megamall is staggering. Whether you're looking for fashion, electronics, home goods, or anything in between, you're sure to find it here. The mall's layout is well-organized, making it easy to navigate through the different sections.

What truly sets Megamall apart is the attention to detail in providing a memorable shopping experience. The cleanliness and maintenance of the facilities are remarkable. Everything is in pristine condition, creating a pleasant atmosphere for shoppers.

The food court is a culinary journey in itself, offering a diverse range of cuisines to suit any palate. It's a great place to take a break and refuel during a shopping spree.

Moreover, the staff members are courteous and ready to assist, making your visit even more enjoyable.

Megamall's central location within the city and its extensive parking facilities add to the convenience.

In summary, Megamall remains a top-tier shopping destination that offers an unmatched shopping experience. With its variety of stores, cleanliness, culinary options, and helpful staff, it deserves a solid 5-star rating for consistently delivering excellence to its visitors.

text.text:
The Mall had a great promising start. It's supposed to cater to the Ayala properties (Avida) and the rest of the subdivisions within the vicinity.

Army+Navy, Wendy's, Seafood Island, Joe Kuan, Adobo Connection, Family Mart, Samsonite, George Optical, LEE/RRJ, L Time Studio, Sw!tch...

The aforementioned are some of the shops and food services that eventually CLOSED in the mall's first years of existence. For them, the market just wasn't there. Tenants came and went faster than expected.

In alphabet or grade terms (i.e., market class), it's more like D than C.

Still hopeful, though, that it would make a turnaround, especially when the pandemic is finally over...

text.text:
Ayala Feliz is a boutique mall in Pasig Marikina area.

Parking Space:

The parking area is very spacious. However, the parking area is poorly designed; it's located on the top floor and has a lot of twists and turns that are prone to accidents. Unfortunately, there were also no parking markers that's why it's hard to locate your parking space.

Stores:

So many stores were permanently closed probably due to bankruptcy from the turbulent economy during the pandemic. A lot of the remaining stores were considered low to mid-range market such as Jollibee, Bench, Penshoppe, Yabu, and etc.

Layout:

The layout is very simple with few grassy areas. This is one Ayala's smallest malls.

Overall:

Not bad for a mall in the east area but it doesn't offer a lot of things that would make people come back again and again.

text.text: Go Hotels Mandaluyong is the perfect budget hotel to stay in when doing business in the metro. With everything almost a Grab ride away, it's the perfect place to recharge before a busy day. The place is surrounded with restaurants, cafes, and convenience stores so everything is literally a stone's throw away. We were also able to try their breakfast and it was hearty and worth it. I also had some deliveries sent and the staff were so kind to keep it while we were stuck in traffic.

text.text: Since I'm on a budget, I chose GoHotel for my staycation after a major operation to convalesce and recuperate in instead of in an airbnb or other budget hotels around Mandaluyong bec this is, by far for me, the best choice. We are staying in a bedroom with twin beds, with a view of Edsa-Pioneer. It has basic amenities just right for me and my daughter's needs bec. we can use the wifi for my work and my daughter's online class. I initially stayed in a room with no window but the room had an imaginary window as a decor. Water dispensers are available at the hallways and a kettle, pitcher and mugs are provided in the rooms. The staff are kind, cheerful, friendly and very accommodating. This branch is a budget bed & breakfast hotel only no other luxurious amenities but very easy on the pocket. I'm loving my stay here.

text.text:
It seems like a backpacker's hotel from the exterior but the rooms are so nice and clean it may pass for a staycation hotel if only it had the proper amenities like pool, gym etc.  Bed and bathroom linen are similar to the ones used in 5 star hotels.  Not a pretentious hotel, though, I believe there are inner rooms that do not have windows.  Our ones had the EDSA view.

They don't have F&B  outlets as such like room service or restaurants; but they do have a refreshment area where there's a fridge with sodas, canned juices, bottled teas and water (may be purchased from the receptionists).  Hot coffee and cup noodles are also available for a fee.

There's parking at the basement, again for a fee but hotel guests get a discount if you pass by the reception, get a coupon before paying at the parking cashier.

description.text: Compact rooms, some with city views, in an informal high-rise hotel featuring a shaded outdoor pool.

formatted_address: C5, corner Target Street, Taguig, Metro Manila, Philippines

text.text: We decided to stay at the hotel for 2 nights. I will tell you it did not disappoint. The staff were very nice and accommodating. Rooms were clean and you can tell that the hotel is pretty new. Especially by the smell. The bed was also comfy and I had a good rest. No water problems either. text.text:
What I loved about this hotel was the architecture and interiors as it is a restored building of the historic Manila Army and Navy Club. Other than that, hotel service and food was generally okay.

Most of the best hotel furniture and interior design can be found in the hallways and lobby. The room we stayed in was decent save for the mismatched furniture. Room service was a bit slow when we asked for additional utensils and extra bedding.

The breakfast buffet was not the best, but it wasn‚Äôt bad either. Staff was very accommodating and even put us in a private dining room since there was a convention going on at the same time in the main dining area.

Our hotel stay was also very quiet and pleasant despite that there was a convention full of people at the time.

Overall, the hotel is best enjoyed for its interiors and architecture whilst lounging at their outdoor patio with a drink. Beyond that, it's generally okay for staying a night or two but don't expect too much.

text.text:
The good:
*Affordable room with basic amenities
*Staff were polite, particularly the receptionist and guard
*They gave my mom a free birthday brownie ala mode

The bad:
*Little stains on the wall and floor
*There were annoying outside noises with their doors that we disturbing the quiet
*Restaurant room service -  we never got our breakfast served, 70 minutes after we requested it (they eventually refunded it) even after we followed up 4 times. They claimed to have a full house but never advised us during our mutliple follow ups that they didn't have the food we were ordering (Tapa) and decided upon themselves to replace the order with Tocino (which my mom doesn't eat) AGAIN without informing us. We would have appreciated a simple heads up instead of making us do multiple follow ups and leaving us hungry and agitated (not good for people with gastritis and a senior citizen).

We received apologies from their managers but we were really disappointed with what happened. Overall, while there were hits and misses with this hotel, that service incident really ruined our otherwise peaceful stay here in Madison 101.

text.text:
Subject: Disappointing Experience Regarding Deposit Policy .

Dear Sir/ Madam,                                                                                     (Hotel Management),

I recently had the opportunity to stay at your esteemed hotel during my return journey from Indonesia to Davao. As a frequent traveler and loyal customer of Agoda, I had high expectations for my stay.

While I found the room to be neat and clean, I was deeply disappointed by the hotel's deposit policy. At the time of check-in, the counter staff insisted on a 2,000 Filipino Pesos deposit, which would be returned upon checkout after room inspection. This practice is not only inconvenient but also disrespectful to guests who have already provided their credit card information through a reliable booking source.

I would like to point out that most of other hotels in the same locality do not have such a policy, making your hotel's approach seem like a lack of confidence in your guests. This was a significant inconvenience and a source of discomfort during my stay.

Due to this experience, I regret to inform you that I cannot recommend your hotel to my friends, colleagues, or anyone in my network for their stay in Manila.

I hope you take this feedback seriously and reconsider your deposit policy to better accommodate and respect your guests in the future.

Sincerely,
farooque Randhawa

text.text:
This is a friendly hotel placed in a usefull location for MOA / City of Dreams and the airport as well as the Department of Foreign Affairs.

It us reasonably easy to access with good parking but very steep ramps upto the parking areas which is above the reception.

They have an outdoor pool under the 7th floor with open sides and a bar thatvis open at night.

The rooms are spacious however - the fridges did not seem to work - they offer a kettle and water but no tea or coffee - the shower gel and siap dispensers were empty and were given bottles.

Sadly breakfast was not as good as expected and when i got my onelette it did not look or actually taste very good.

WOULD I RECOMMEND - yes for a short stay it serves a great purpose.

WILL I VISIT AGAIN - maybe if needs occur.

text.text:
My recent stay at Wynwood Hotel Manila was an experience that perfectly blended modern sophistication with urban flair. Located in the heart of the bustling city, this hotel offers a stylish and comfortable stay for both business and leisure travelers.

First impressions matter, and Wynwood Hotel Manila didn't disappoint. The lobby exuded an air of chic elegance, featuring contemporary decor and inviting seating areas. The check-in process was swift and efficient, with the staff greeting us warmly and providing all necessary information about the hotel's amenities and services.

The room we stayed in was spacious and tastefully decorated, boasting a minimalist design that radiated a sense of tranquility. The plush bed ensured a good night's sleep, and the room's cleanliness and attention to detail were commendable. Additionally, the panoramic city views from our window were a delightful sight, especially during the evening when the city lights lit up the skyline.

The hotel's dining options were satisfactory, though I felt there could have been a wider range of choices on the menu. The breakfast buffet offered a decent selection of both local and international dishes, ensuring a satisfying start to the day. The on-site restaurant had an inviting ambiance, though it lacked some of the flair and variety I had expected from a hotel of this caliber.

Wynwood Hotel Manila does shine in terms of recreational facilities. The rooftop pool area was a definite highlight, providing a cool and relaxing retreat amidst the hustle and bustle of the city. The gym was well-equipped with modern exercise machines, perfect for those who wish to stay active during their stay.

One aspect that stood out during our stay was the exceptional customer service provided by the hotel staff. From the concierge to the housekeeping team, every staff member we encountered was friendly, helpful, and attentive to our needs. They were knowledgeable about the local attractions and were more than willing to provide recommendations for dining and sightseeing.

The hotel's location is also a major advantage, being within walking distance or a short ride from popular shopping districts, cultural landmarks, and entertainment hubs. This convenience allowed us to explore the vibrant city easily and make the most of our stay in Manila.

However, one minor drawback was the occasional noise from the nearby streets, which might be an issue for light sleepers. While the hotel itself is well-insulated, the sounds of the bustling city occasionally filtered into our room.

Wynwood Hotel Manila offered a chic and comfortable stay in a prime location. With its modern aesthetics, friendly staff, and convenient amenities, it's an excellent choice for travelers looking for a stylish urban escape. While there is room for improvement in some areas, the overall experience was enjoyable and would undoubtedly entice me to consider staying at Wynwood Hotel Manila again in the future.

text.text:
First time to stay in the property (2 - 5) and I loved the way they handled my queries when I inquired walking in.  The rooms and amenities were what expected in a three star hotel including the mini fridge kettle, cups, glass, plates and flatware. Location was perfect and the roof deck space was a nice touch.

The flexibility of the hours of stay was very convenient.

However, what did not work for me was the pest control and maintenance of the amenities. There were small cockroaches coming out from the woodwork in the 7th floor room initially assigned to me.  As well as the defective heater and ground I got touching the pipe. Safe wasn't working and the aircon filter was quite dirty.

Reporting it, the admin made time to have the heater checked. The staff to check the safe was on his day-off.

They provided me the option to transfer which I took. Heater and aircon worked and clean. The number of cockroaches were minimized but still  there. The safe still was not working. It was disappointing.

I would encourage the admin to pay attention to the details for this wonderful place

Overlooking these, the property is still a better choice compare to the nearby areas due to the nearby access to a huge mall.  I would still comeback and stay.

Hope it helps.

text.text:
Absolute worst experience with customer service.
-
We usually bring foreign guests here who come in for quick visits. A recent visit left us with no choice but to book a room because our guests checked in at around 1am and we had to leave at 5am to go to the airport.
-
We'd already booked a room when the security guard told us that there were no parking spaces available. We also could not have our room refunded on the spot, and they just told us to request a refund via email.
-
What made things worse was the security guard kept on insisting that he told us that the parking spaces are first come first served‚Äî which was a total lie because they did not say such a thing, and even if they did, this is absolutely useless because they did not inform us that there were no available parking spaces anymore during that time.
-
They neglected to tell us that there were no available parking spaces, even though they saw that we had a car. They were being defensive and kept on pushing the lie that we had been informed before booking a room. We had offered to just double park in the topmost floor's parking spot and that they could call our room if the occupying vehicle was going to leave, but they would not listen to any of our suggestions.
-
We were dead tired. But we were not made to feel welcome.
-
A simple apology would have been welcome and readily accepted, but they kept on insisting we were wrong for not knowing about the parking situation and that they told us it was first come first served, yet again, no mention of this before we booked a room. Infuriating and embarassing.
-
Long story short, we chose to just remain in the car and not use the hotel room because of the many valuables belonging to our foreign guests inside the car which we cannot bring up to the hotel room because of the sheer size and number of items.
-
Eventually, we emailed for a refund, but as expected‚Äî due to the already terrible management issues plaguing this establishment‚Äî we were denied the refund.
-
Terrible management and neglectful staff training by Red Planet all around. Please do not come here if you value a hassle free experience. Because they will turn small, rectifiable incidents into palpable hell for you.

text.text:
We booked a superior room in agoda and it was shown there that a bathtub was included, but there was no bathtub when we checked in to our room. However I called the front desk and raised our concern to them, and they accommodated our request and transfered us to the room that we were really expecting. So, good customer service on their part!

The breakfast buffet is superb! Cafe Miranda has a very good and welcoming staff. They are attentive to our needs and offer foods that are to our liking.

The location is very convenient as well. They have free parking but be sure to be fine with parking on the sidewalk.

And a little tip, if you're the type who drinks a lot of water, then I suggest that you bring your own! We tried calling room service to request for more water and they told us to try calling Cafe Miranda instead to request for service water because they only replace the complimentary water once a day. So, we called the restaurant and they only gave us one glass of cold water. We had to go to the 7/11 nearby to buy a large bottle of water.

But overall, it was still an enjoyable and a pleasant stay. We'll give it a 4/5 stars!!!!

text.text:
It was just an overnight stay for business. Checking-in took longer than usual because apparently the hotel was fully-booked at the time. The lobby was not too comfortable.

We were in the hotel for an activity. Food served was not that impressive and the function room was too cold and bit dim lit. We stayed in that function room for two days.

The room OK, but LOVE their bed and pillows --- so COMFY!!! However, the TV cable service is not too impressive --- too many channels that are not included in their subscription, and they didn't have a TV channel list so you don't have an idea which channel is ok and you are forced to channel surf to find something to watch.

Restaurant is open til 11pm only. Tried their pizza, it was GREAT! I forgot the name of the pizza though, sorry.

Location is in the middle of the busy Manila business district of Mabini-Ermita area. The road is quite narrow, so expect lot of traffic, but there are a lot of business establishments around.

In general, the staff were fine.

name: Makati Palace Hotel

description.text: Refined, high-rise hotel with an indoor-outdoor pool, plus a gym, dining and a 24-hour spa.

formatted_address: 5011 P. Burgos, corner Caceres, Makati 1200, Metro Manila, Philippines

text.text:
AVOID this hotel. Cockroach and other small insects infested!
We checked in and the process was extremely slow and laborious, there was only one lady on reception and about 15 guests trying to check in, when we finally got seen to after about 20-25 mins we still didn‚Äôt have our rooms and were asked to sit and wait for an indefinite timeframe.
Then after about another 15 minutes we finally got the keys to our room.
We were taken to our room by the only helpful person around the bellboy. The lifts took a long time and there was no display in the lifts to say what floor you were on. The rooms were very old, dirty and smelly. We were not happy with the rooms as they did not reflect what was advertised on the website. We went to reception and paid to upgrade to the ‚Äúrenovated‚Äù rooms.
Whilst these initially looked better they were far from clear, there were balls of hair and dust everywhere, when I walked in the room I was instantly greeted by a cockroach. I thought it might be a one off but as I walked through the room more roaches appeared and other small insects that were biting. The final straw was when I sat on the bed and a cockroach joined me in there too!
I did not stay the night and checked out into another hotel. The staff did not care less and looking at the reviews they have made no attempt to improve the cleanliness and hygiene in this hotel.
There are many other much nicer hotels around for no additional cost.

text.text:
The Makati Palace Hotel, is nothing like a Palace it is a rundown old outdated hotel that needs to be ripped down and replaced.

There are two parts to this hotel very old dirty smelly cockroach infested rooms in the oldest part and then the part they call the renovated Park which is still very old but at least they have had some showers replaced and otherwise the furnishings and everything old and outdated.

They provide two very small bottles of free bottled water dental kits,¬† slippers, tissues, a safe and a bar fridge which actually works well and keeps things cold.

They do not provide face washers or bathrobes.

The older rooms are disgraceful, and they are stale smelly old and everything is well past its use by date and is uncomfortable. And the old rooms only have a very old shower over bath which looks like it came off Noah's Ark.

I complained them was subsequently moved to the so-called renovated area where there has been a lick of paint added but still the furnishings original old outdated furnishings.

The bathroom hand basin has terrible water pressure it is just a trickle, and the toilet handgun is the same with very poor water pressure and the toilet doesn't flush properly.

The only positive thing I could say for this place was the shower as it has a high pressure shower head with good water pressure nothing else in this hotel is up to standard.

The Wi-Fi is very poor quality and regularly cuts out and they have a very small old LCD TV with a reasonable selection of English speaking channels.

The swimming pool area is unsightly and the water in the pool is cloudy and disgusting and I'm sure you would get there or I infections if you did swim in their terrible water.

The lifts feel unsafe as they shake and there is no air conditioning or fan inside the lifts they are hot, stuffy old and grubby

I would not recommend this hotel to anybody there are too many far better properties at cheaper prices or similar price in the area.

My overall impression is this hotel needs to be demolished and something new rebuilt in its place it is well past its use by date it is not comfortable and it is not worth the money.

text.text:
Oasis in the middle of historic Bukhara

The hotel is set in a narrow street, off a busy boulevard right off the center of old Bukhara. It doesn't look like much but once you are inside the lobby leads to a small courtyard, an over street passage and another courtyard.

There is a lot to like about this hotel and it is very popular with visitors to Bukhara. It is very near much of old Bukhara but not in the middle of the busy streets and market. You can walk to everything yet feel like you are in a quieter part of town. There are several markets and restaurants near the hotel.

The staff is exceptional good, they would stand up and say "hi," ask how my visit was going every time I came back from a walk. Everyone from the cleaning lady to the the wonderful lady who made the exceptional breakfast every day was friendly and kind.

My room was very spacious, the bed was very comfortable ( I like a firm mattress)). There was a small fridge in the room and the hotel offered tea or coffee in your room or better yet, on the rooftop terrace.

This is a wonderful place to stay if you are in Bukhara, and if you travel to Uzbekistan, you should definitely stay in Bukhara. It was probably my favorite city in Uzbekistan, the old city is intact and most of the sights in the same area, easy walking distance from the hotel. I would highly recommend the Amelia Hotel.

text.text: VERY DISAPPOINTED. I WILL NEVER RECOMMEND Richmonde Hotel to all people I will meet.. Checked-in October 13, 2023 evening at Room 2203. The Front Desk did not give instructions on how to use the elevator using the room key card. October 13-14, the cold shower knob was a bit loose thread though there was water running through and I was able to use it. However, on October 15 at 11am, I was balancing the hot shower with cold shower and I was able to wet my hair and body, had shampoo and soap. Suddenly, the cold shower knob was fully loose thread and no cold water running through, only hot shower was functional. I got out of the bath tub and used the bidet to rinse my shampooed hair and body soaked in soap. I phoned the reception and spoke to Miss Shanice or Shania, the Duty Manager. All she can do and say was to apologize and report to maintenance. I did not feel the sense of urgency on how she handled my concern. We checked -out at 1pm, I did not feel sincerity nor personal touch in pacifying an inconvenienced customer. Very poor customer service. I regret that I gave an overall excellent rating for Richmonde Hotel done on October 14 when I was handed the survey form while having my breakfast at the dining hall. Your maintenance department is not doing a good job performing routine checks.

text.text:
So we are always booking our activities here since the hotel is very convenient to our participants until an incident happened at their limited parking space. My staff was approached by a hotel manager and told us that I should move my car because the parking space that I took was exclusive ONLY for their hotel service (no sign or whatsoever that it was a space for their service and their parking space was only good for 5 to 6 cars by the way) while to think, the polite security guard was the one who assisted me to park freely there. With my dissapointment, I told my staff to tell the hotel manager that I am their guest and why should I be the one adjusting for their service and then, suddenly, the manager acted weird and looking at us like she wanted our activity to end, so that all of our parked cars can already leave their hotel (This happened just yesterday by this date of writing this review).

The hotel staff and security guards who were assisting us in their conference room was a relief though because they're very helpful and attentive with our concerns unlike the hotel manager.

Overall, this hotel is not good if you have a vehicle because their reserving it to their hotel service / delivery trucks instead of their guests (we are always booking our meetings here by the way ) the fact that their parking space is very limited. Probably, I will not anymore get this hotel for our agency's set of activities because of the rude actions showed by the hotel manager. No thanks! üëé

The Regent hotel is an absolutely amazing place to stay. From the moment you walk in, you are greeted with warm hospitality and a welcoming atmosphere. The staff is friendly, attentive, and always ready to assist with anything you may need during your stay.

The rooms are spacious, comfortable, and elegantly decorated, with all the amenities you could ask for, from luxurious bedding to high-speed internet access. The views are breathtaking, whether you're looking out over the city skyline or the ocean.

The hotel's facilities are top-notch, with a fitness center, swimming pool, and spa that will help you unwind and rejuvenate after a long day of work or sightseeing. The dining options are exceptional, with a wide range of cuisine available to suit every taste and occasion.

Overall, the Regent hotel is a fantastic choice for anyone looking for a luxurious, relaxing, and unforgettable experience. I would highly recommend this hotel to anyone looking for a world-class stay in a beautiful location.

text.text:
The location was top notch, just a few steps away from Robinsons Galleria. I requested for a quiet room, which was largely met. The bed was very spacious (it could easily fit three people) and comfortable. The airconditioning was just right (not super cold or warm). Check out was fast and efficient. Elevator service was also fast, and the guard at the entrance was nice and polite. Greatly appreciated the water dispenser by the elevators and the soap dispensers (good sustainability features).

However, the soundproofing of the room was not very good -- one could easily hear the noise from the halls (although the sounds from the adjacent rooms could not be heard). There were small cockroaches in the room, especially in the sink area -- I was able to kill about 7 of them during my stay and just ignored the others. I usually sleep with the lights turned off, but because of the cockroach problem, I had to sleep with some of the lights on for fear of some of them crawling on me while I was asleep. There were some spaces in the 4th floor that had a random piece of wood propped up, which made the whole space look untidy and unprofessional. There was only one person manning the reception counter at 8pm, so check in took some time (not a very good experience if one just came from a whole day of tiring travel).

All in all, okay for just one night's sleep.

text.text:
The Manila Prince Hotel
We stayed at the Manila Prince Hotel for twenty-three days while getting married and later, sightseeing.
I give an overall 5 out of 5 Star rating for the exceptional service, rooms, and hospitality.
There was free breakfast for guests every morning at the Marcelino St. Caf√© located inside of the hotel.  Every morning we were greeted by friendly faces, and by the third day, they had coffee and orange juice on the table in advance.  They already knew our order.
The front desk staff was very friendly and polite.  They helped us often with arranging transportation and advice on where to explore.
The room support staff was remarkable as they not only cleaned and vacuumed the rooms each day, but also provided bottled water.
Our suite was amazing with two bathrooms.  One with a shower and a tub, and one with a standup shower and a jacuzzi tub. There was a large living room with a couch and table that allowed us to eat with visiting family.  I would only suggest adding a microwave in the rooms.  This would allow guests to reheat leftovers.
The hotel pool was fun, had beautiful waterfalls, and was well stocked with towels for the guests.
If you are planning a trip to Manila, put the Manila Prince Hotel at the top of your list.

text.text:
This is a very good hotel to stay in when in Tagaytay.

The rooms are very clean and comfortable. The minimalist interior design of the rooms is perfect for rest and relaxation, not to mention the lovely view of Taal lake from the balcony.

Staff was courteous and helpful, very responsive to our needs.

My only complaint were the cafe and restaurant. Drinks and snacks at the cafe seemed overpriced. The breakfast buffet at the restaurant was so-so.

Dinner service at the restaurant was non-existent. We arrived for dinner very early; we were the only diners at the time. Two hours later not a single dish had been served and there were also several other guests already waiting for their orders as well. We ended up canceling our order and dining elsewhere.

Overall, location and rooms are excellent for a few nights stay. Skip their food service. For a hotel supposedly managed by Enderun, it was quite disappointing.

text.text:
Great place to stay around Tagaytay area. It does not have any Taal Volcano view since it's on the other side of the road but I would say it has a good room, accommodating service and relaxing location. If you're coming from Sta. Rosa exit of Calax, it would be around 45 minutes to get there without any traffic along Tagaytay mainroad. Arriving at the place, there is a security check point where you need to provide your valid ID. I also discovered that they also have some those renting and owned units so I don't know the review there. (Maybe some time). For the hotel stay experience, it was beautiful. We arrived late but there's an available front desk for check in. There's also a lot of covered parking spaces. There were also elevators to take us in our rooms at 3F. Rooms have their own air conditioning units, TVs, heater at the washroom (Please revisit all equipment if working well esp for room 302) and some complimentary items. When we booked via Booking, we didn't get with the free breakfast, however it didn't hold us to have a good meal beside the hotel (less than 20 steps from the main door) to start the day. They have very limited choices but it was nice since it was a good deal. There's a swimming pool and forest facilities though I didn't try to swim and explore. Hoping I can be back for another good hotel experience.

To add they have function rooms and outdoor space. Contact them to get the details.

text.text:
I recently had the pleasure of staying here at La bella boutique hotel nestled in a serene pine forest, and I couldn't have been more delighted with my experience. The Santorini-inspired architecture added a touch of Mediterranean elegance to the tranquil surroundings. The scent of pine in the air was refreshing, and the view of towering trees from my room was simply enchanting.

The hotel's attention to detail was evident throughout my stay. The interior decor seamlessly blended Santorini's iconic white and blue hues, creating a calming and sophisticated atmosphere. The staff's warm hospitality made me feel right at home, and their recommendations for nearby coffee shops added an extra layer of convenience and delight to my mornings.

Speaking of coffee shops, the ones surrounding the hotel were an absolute gem. Each offered a unique and cozy ambiance, perfect for enjoying a leisurely cup of coffee while soaking in the natural beauty that surrounded me. It was a delightful way to start my days and unwind in the evenings.

Overall, my experience at this Santorini-inspired boutique hotel surrounded by pine trees and delightful coffee shops was nothing short of magical. If you're seeking a peaceful escape with a touch of Mediterranean charm, I wholeheartedly recommend a stay here.

text.text:
My partner and I stayed at The Lake Hotel from June 30 to July 2, and unfortunately, our experience left much to be desired. While the staff was attentive and professional and the view fantastic, the overall stay was marred by several room issues that impacted our enjoyment.

The most concerning problem, was the presence of black mold in the room, likely due to a ceiling leak. Not only did this raise health concerns, but it also made us question the hotel's cleanliness and maintenance practices. The shower also had drainage issues and emitted an unpleasant odor, making it an uncomfortable experience.

In addition to that, we encountered insects in the room and noticed a lack of proper cleaning upon check-in, which was disappointing (there were dead insects by the window, live insects flying around, and some sort of film on the tiled floor).

Another letdown was the wine served during our stay. Both the red and white wines were unpleasantly aged and undrinkable.

To make matters worse, we reached out to the hotel asking for the manager's email a few days ago to express our concerns, but regrettably, we received no response, leaving us feeling ignored and disheartened.

Jet-lagged and exhausted from a 25-hour flight, we should‚Äôve reported these instances immediately. However, after seeing such positive reviews when booking this hotel, we expected a higher level of service and cleanliness. Unfortunately, our experience fell short, and the unresponsive management further compounded our disappointment.

We hope this review will prompt the hotel to address these issues and improve their guest experience. As of now, we cannot recommend this hotel and hope our feedback will be taken seriously for future guests' sake.

text.text:
This is a hotel with poor service, poor facilities, and false pet-friendliness. Trust me, any pet friendly hotel is better than this one.
Believe me, this hotel is currently the worst pet-friendly hotel I have ever stayed in. We booked a pet-friendly double room for 6000 plus per night, which is close to 7000p per night, but when we checked in, he temporarily informed us that pets would cost extra even though they charged extra.  They pay for pets but they are not friendly to pets at all. They don‚Äôt even provide drinking water for pets.

We spent nearly 7000p. The lake view room we booked turned out to be a connecting room at the end.
The hotel was under construction and close to the road. It was very noisy.
The door lock was broken.
There was a thick layer of ash in the bathroom.
There was no one-time service provided by a star-rated hotel.
Toiletries, bed sheets and duvet covers are not new.
Only 2 bath towels are provided. The toilet paper is not new and has been used by others.
The floor at the door is bulging and it is very difficult to open the door.
The TV does not have any channels. When it comes to breakfast, it is very annoying because we have a small dog, so we chose  Sitting outside on the lawn there was no service at all and we were not even given napkins and later I found out there were no people around with dogs and they were all served water a range of services only us no cutlery no service water and after we had just finished and were ready to drink coffee  When the waiter came over very eagerly to take away our plates and cutlery, I thought they were replacing new cutlery for us, but they did not collect the cutlery. I hope we hotel guests will leave quickly. The buffet feels like a lot of leftover food from the night before.  It‚Äôs not a new hotel. Except for poor facilities, poor service, poor hygiene, and expensive price, it can‚Äôt even compare to the island hotel where I went to surf. For the most honest review, please see the picture.

formatted_address: Bacoor, Cavite, Philippines

text.text:
First of all there is gender inequality that is going on with this hotel. So you see, we are trying to find a place to sleep last night and we found this horrible hotel with lots of good reviews that's why we decided to choose this hotel to spend the night.

So we are three guests that would like to check in. I am with my brother and my sister. The staff told me that "Tatlo pala kayo? Akala ko dalawa lang kayo. Hindi kayo pwede kung tatlo." And we asked why since we are willing to pay for the additional head naman and we are all siblings then the staff replied "Dalawa kasi lalaki. Kung dalawa sana yung babae tapos isang lalaki pwede pero hindi pwede kapag dalawang lalaki tapos isang babae".

Come on we are siblings, we already presented our IDs but the staff is insisting that only two girls and 1 boy can stay. After that one, we spoke with a supervisor and raised our concern. They already allowed us to stay.

Then after a few minutes we got a call from the awful frontdesk. She was asking about the money that I gave the staff. We were discussing about the additional head and she asked me that I gave a "2500 deposit" then I aswered no. What I gave the staff is the payment and they never asked for a deposit. But that rude lady on the phone told me, "yung 2.5k po na binigay niyo is yung deposit niyo po" then I replied, "ay sorry po, bali yung 2.5k ko po kasi is yung payment po for the room and I didn't consider it as a deposit kasi di ba po ang deposit is makukuha niyo po once you checked out?" She replied, "payment and deposit is the same thing po. Ang gulo niyo po kausap (With a rude tone of voice)." Like what? I know there are times na magkakaroon ng misunderstanding thru the phone with the management and customers but then that is not the correct tone and response that you should be using while you are having a conversation with your customers. Malay ko ba na magkaiba kami ng definition ng payment and deposit? üòè

Anyways, I don't recommend this hotel. Find another one who will treat you better and make you feel important.

text.text:
Hotel Kimberly Tagaytay made our 10th year wedding anniversary unforgettable! The staff, especially Ms. Jersey, was incredibly accommodating and professional. text.text:
We recently had the most enchanting stay at  Hotel Kimberly Tagaytay, a family-&-pet-friendly hotel! From the moment my family and I checked in, we knew it was going to be a memorable experience. The staff were incredibly welcoming with their warm smiles.

One of the highlights of our stay was the delightful surprise we received after dinner. As we returned to our room after the long fun day of hotel activities (cooking demo, parlor games, scavenger hunt, & movie night), there was an unexpected knock at the door, and to our delight, we were presented with a kiddie nightcap: a glass of milk and a set of Oreos for each of our kids. It was an incredibly thoughtful gesture that made our evening extra special.

That was after dinner - savoring a mouthwatering dinner. We had Beef Bulalo and crispy pork belly, which were expertly seasoned, perfectly cooked, and truly exceptional.

The room itself was cozy and beautifully designed, providing a peaceful retreat for our family. The attention to detail in every aspect of the hotel was evident, from the kid-&-pet friendly amenities to the impeccable cleanliness.

On top of all the wonderful experiences, the hotel has HEATED pools. With Tagatay‚Äôs cold weather, the ability to take a refreshing dip in a warm pool added an extra layer of luxury.

If you're looking for a place that goes above and beyond to ensure your family's comfort and happiness, this is the perfect place for you. It's a true gem in the world of family (including pets) hospitality, and we can't wait to return for another unforgettable stay.

This is our go-to place for no frills Filipino comfort food. Their silogs are good and the servings are reasonably generous. My only minor complaint is that the ‚Äòsi‚Äô part is just plain rice, and not ‚Äòsinangag‚Äô (fried rice). But still, it‚Äôs a hearty meal.

Their bulalo is good too. Their other dishes like the pinakbet, lato salad, and deep-fried baby crabs are also straight forward Filipino dishes cooked at home style‚Äîwhich is the best way to prepare Filipino food: no twists, no gimmicks, and no pretensions.

Vivian‚Äôs gives us that, that is why we always come back to this place for a hearty good ol‚Äô Filipino breakfast or lunch. It‚Äôs one of my family‚Äôs favorite restaurants. I wouldn‚Äôt trade it for a Sarsa or Locavore.

text.text:
The Quezon Heritage House
The reconstructed house of the Quezon family is an intimate look at the day-to-day life of the President of the Commonwealth and his family. It is interesting to see the decorations and furniture in the time when there were no big industrialized factories.

text.text:
I toured the Quezon Heritage House on Saturday, June 3.  As a foreigner, I must admit that I am not entirely familiar with the history of the Philippines and of President Quezon -- so much of the  information delivered to me by the tour guides / interns / was completely new to me. However, I was sure of one mistake made by the tour guides: they informed me that President Quezon and the Philippines had saved/rescued Jews from Israel. Despite having pointed out the flaws in this statement, the tour guides refused to acknowledge the possibility that their tour included inaccurate information.  (Especially given that President Quezon's amazing work with Jewish populations from Germany and Europe occurred in the 1930s, while Israel was formally established in 1948, after the conclusion of Word War II.)

Given that I know the tour guides provided me information that is clearly false on the one topic I knew something about, I doubt that everything they told me was accurate.

The (re-constructed) house is pretty to look at, but I would probably skip the tour.

text.text:
The Quezon Heritage House is a historical landmark located in the city of Quezon in the Philippines. It is the ancestral home of the country's second President, Manuel L. Quezon, and is now a museum that showcases his life and legacy.

The house was built in the early 1920s and was designed by renowned architect Juan Nakpil. It was originally located in Gilmore, Quezon City, but was moved to its current location in the Quezon Memorial Circle in 2003.

The Quezon Heritage House features original furniture, paintings, and other memorabilia from the Quezon family. Visitors can take a guided tour of the house and learn about the life and accomplishments of Manuel L. Quezon, who is known for his efforts in securing Philippine independence from the United States.

In addition to the main house, there are also several other structures on the grounds, including a replica of the house's original chapel and a guesthouse. The Quezon Heritage House is open to the public and is a popular destination for tourists and history buffs alike.

In addition to the main house, there are also several other structures on the grounds, including a replica of the house's original chapel and a guesthouse. The Quezon Heritage House is open to the public and is a popular destination for tourists and history buffs alike.

text.text: Guadalupe Church, Makati City - it‚Äôs a 400 years old structure with an amazing facade. Founded by the Augustinians, the construction of its foundation was laid in 1601 and was finished in 1629. Some parts of this church were rebuilt several times because of the earthquakes; and in 1880 the masonry roof collapsed because of the earthquake so it was rebuilt in 1882 by Rev. Jose Corujedo O.S.A. Later, this structure was burnt during the fight between Filipinos and Americans on February 1899. It was reconstructed and re-opened to the public in 1983. Review 08/2014

text.text:
The shrine is located in former military barracks that were reconstructed and adopted to serve as a museum in 1953.
Most revered national hero dr Jose Rizal spent his last days imprisoned there before his public execution on December 29, 1896. The museum showcases Jose Rizal‚Äôs prison cell, his trial room. Among the exhibits are the alcohol stove in which he hid his poem Mi ultimo adios, his vertebrae (where the bullet hit him), his coat, hat, case and more.
Worth visiting. The entrance is free once you are in Fort Santiago.

text.text: Rizal Shrine at Fort Santiago honors the Philippines'national hero, Dr. Jose Rizal. There is a big statue of the man in the middle of the fort as well as a museum. There is no entrance fee, but knowledge is priceless and the bulk of information you will get about this wise man is priceless. The museum has almost everything about Rizal, from his early childhood, family life, education, love of arts and sciences, love life, accomplishments, and death. You can find artifacts, reprints, memorabilias, and videos that provide information about this Filipino hero. The museum is inside Fort Santiago so you need to acess it first. You will need about an hour to tour the whole museum and really understand what it showcases.

name: Quezon Memorial Shrine

description.text: 217-ft. memorial & shrine dedicated to former President Manuel Quezon, with a museum at its base.

formatted_address: M22X+874, Quezon Ave, Diliman, Quezon City, Metro Manila, Philippines

text.text:
The Quezon City Memorial Circle is a fantastic place to visit if you're looking for a relaxing and peaceful atmosphere. As a group of five old friends, we decided to go there to destress and reconnect with nature, and we were not disappointed.

The first thing that struck us was the sheer size of the park. It's a sprawling green oasis in the heart of the city, offering plenty of space for everyone to unwind. We found various spots to sit, chat, and reminisce about old times. The lush trees and well-maintained lawns provided a refreshing break from the urban hustle and bustle.

For those interested in history, the Quezon City Memorial Circle also houses the Quezon Memorial Shrine. The monument is an impressive tribute to the first president of the Philippines, Manuel L. Quezon. We took some time to explore the museum inside the shrine and learn about Quezon's contributions to the country's development.

Another great aspect of the memorial circle is the availability of various outdoor activities. We rented bicycles and rode around the park, enjoying the fresh air and scenic views. There are also picnic areas where you can bring your own food and have a leisurely lunch amidst nature.

Overall, our visit to the Quezon City Memorial Circle was a rejuvenating experience. It's a perfect getaway for groups of friends or families seeking a break from the city's hustle. The park offers a serene ambiance, recreational activities, and a touch of history, making it an ideal destination for anyone looking to destress and spend quality time with loved ones.

At the base is the chronological events of heroes, including former Philippine President Manuel Quezon, engraved in the marble.

Inside the marble monument is the entrance to the Manuel Quezon Museum, but the public viewing is limited to weekend.

At night, you can see the illumination of the Memorial Tower.

At the surrounding area is the biking, walking, running, and jogging area.

name: The Dungeons of Fort Santiago
formatted_address: HXW9+2R8, Gen Mona St Cor Sta Clara St Fort Santiago Maestranza, Brgy 655 Zone 69, Manila 1032, Metro Manila, Philippines

text.text: Very surreal, sad, emotional, yet a great educational place to visit inside Fort Santiago at Intramuros.  It was originally built for arms storage during the war, but converted to a prison in 1715.  Sadly, over 600 decomposing bodies were discovered by the US Army during the liberation of Manila in 1945.  It's an eerie feeling to feel how how small this place was and how 600 bodies were kept here.  You're free to walk around and take pictures, they just ask you respect the history and the deceased.

text.text: Located inside Fort Santiago, the dungeons (historical landmark) holds so many stories of our Philippine history. It played so much role with our old society. Its currently maintained and preserved by the government to keep the history alive. One can explore the dungeons via its original tunnels. It gives me a visual reality check of how the life of the prisoners was back then. Its not just a regular prison - imagine the heat and exposure - what a torture.

text.text:
In Fort Santiago's dungeons deep,
Where pain and suffering ran so steep,
The imprisoned suffered, day and night,
Their cries for freedom, a haunting sight.

From Spanish chains to Japanese rule,
Their spirits brave, their hearts still full,
Of hope and love, and dreams of home,
Amidst the darkness, they didn't roam.

Their memory lives on in this place,
A testament to their courage and grace,
We honor their sacrifice, we remember their pain,
In their memory, let freedom forever reign.

name: Manila American Cemetery and Memorial

description.text: Tranquil, 152-acre cemetery with 17,206 graves, the majority for U.S. soldiers killed during WWII.

formatted_address: 1634 McKinley Rd, Taguig, Metro Manila, Philippines

text.text:
I had a unique and memorable experience at the Manila American Cemetery and Memorial, situated right in the heart of the BGC area. This hidden gem, often less explored, made my visit all the more special, thanks to the pleasant weather, mild cool breeze, and overcast skies (humidity aside).

The meticulous documentation of World War II and the vital roles played by both America and the Philippines truly impressed me. The detailed accounts of those who served during the war provided a deep insight into history.

Moreover, the property is exceptionally well maintained, adding to the overall experience. Visiting this memorial was a departure from the usual tourist spots and offered me a different perspective on history.

text.text:
The Josel Rizal Monument stands tall as a remarkable testament to the Philippines' commitment to preserving its rich and complex history. This monument is more than just a structure of stone; it's a living archive of the tumultuous past that shaped this nation.

What makes the monument truly fascinating is the way it encapsulates both Spanish colonial history and the resilience of the Filipino people. It's a symbol of the enduring spirit of the Philippines, honoring a national hero who fought for independence from Spanish rule. In this one monument, you can see the convergence of these historical forces.

As you stand before it, you can't help but feel a sense of awe and reverence. You're not just witnessing a physical structure; you're stepping into the pages of history. The monument's grandeur mirrors the significance of the events it represents.

Visiting the Josel Rizal Monument is not just sightseeing; it's a journey through time. It's a poignant reminder of the struggles and triumphs that have defined the Philippines. It's a place where history comes to life, and where the past is beautifully and poignantly archived for all to see. If you want to truly understand the heart and soul of the Philippines, this monument is a must-visit.

name: Jose P. Laurel Ancestral House
formatted_address: 1515 Penafrancia, Paco, Manila, Metro Manila, Philippines

text.text: Residence of the Philippine president Jose P. Laurel who was at the highest office of the land during the Imperial Japanese occupation of the country. This house located at a corner of a street in the district of Paco, Manila is seemingly uninhabited though also untouched by the passage of time. The Laurels have been a mainstay of Philippine political life with the son of elder Laurel, Jose Laurel III being an ambassador to Japan during the Marcos Administration and Salvador Laurel being the last prime minister of the Philippines before the position was abolished.

text.text:
Plaza Lacson is part of the historic district of Manila. These days, it's filled with street food vendors and 'bazaar style shops'. It's a stone throw away from historic Escolta, Chinatown, and Quiapo.

It's lively, busy, and dense, yet gives you a glimpse of the life of the average Filipino.

If that is not your type of activity, then turn around and go elsewhere. As with any other trip, just be mindful of your stuff.

text.text:
If you're looking for a great place to hang out and enjoy some delicious drinks and appetizers, OZ Bar at Holiday Inn and Suites Makati is definitely worth checking out. The staff, particularly Winnie and Raymond, are friendly and welcoming, making you feel right at home.

The appetizers are definitely a highlight, with a range of options that are both tasty and satisfying. But the real star of the show here is the cocktails - the mojo and mojito are must-tries, and are sure to leave you feeling refreshed and satisfied. Overall, if you're in the area and looking for a fun and relaxed atmosphere, OZ Bar is definitely worth a visit.

text.text:
Went to Oz bar for a chill night, the lighting and sounds are wonderful.

I was expecting a better view of the city since it was located in a rooftop but that wasnt the case. Although you may get a good view of Holiday Inn's swimming pool and gym if you stay outdoors.

This place is a good place for a grouo who wants to have drinks and chat since the music isnt too loud and not much crowd on weeknights. However, food-wise it was just ok (at least those that we ordered).

We got the new york style pizza (P520+) and i commend the toppings and cheese because it was alot, but not thin crust though. We also got the vegetable somosa (P320+) which is good... and lastly we got the chicken fingers (P420+) which i dont recommend because it was oily and the batter is too thick.

Overall, food price is expensive (for appetizers) as you may have seen on the prices above mainly because it has a chill ambience and located at the roofdeck of a hotel.

text.text: This place is quite a delighter but I could be biased. I was in the "detention room" which is a tucked away man cave with perhaps the widest range of whisky, brandy and rums I ve seen in Manila. The owner himself is a great host and loves talking about drams while we sipped on some Arran 18 Scotch. Only downside if you are gluttonous kinds while drinking alcohol, then there are no food options. But delighter again was that they have their own resto across the street and got us wagyu cubes in less than 30 mins. The bartender "Nima" was humble, curious and great with service. She knows her whisky too üòâ... All in all super impressed. Going back there soon!

text.text:
Poor customer service: people working at the front desk seemed to hate their job so much that they were taking it out to the customers.

Dirty restroom:  no flush for urinals so the smell lingers in the air.  Not sure when the place was last cleaned.

Unfriendly and sarcastic staff:  they kept on opening the door suddenly without excusing themselves.  Not sure what they were trying to do but that was very distracting and an act that showed how little they care about their customers.  Not to mention how they were always glaring at us from the outside.  If it's just a glance that's fine, but glaring was just too much.  We were asking questions about the food and equipment but they probably hated answering it professionally so we only got sarcastic responses.

Old and malfunctioning equipment and lights:  faded text on the remote control and no instructions from the staff on how to use it.  You should ask them first because they don't know the word responsibility.  The keyboard that was supposed to help in place of the remote was actually just a decoration because it's not working and they even blamed the previous customers for breaking it.  I wonder what they said about us after leaving the place?  The room only had dimmed lighting because the other light switch was no longer working so we used our phones' flashlight instead.

TL;DR:  Overall, my experience with the place is terrible and I will never go back to this establishment again.

text.text:
On the outside, it's Pink's Hot Dog BGC. Behind the film and glamor curtains, it's actually a speakeasy located near ShangriLa by the Fort, just try to find the line of restaurants and coffee places at the basement area, and you should be able to find the Pink Hot Dog stand.

Once behind the curtains, you'll see a bar, and some benches. It's super simple and no frills, unlike Bank Bar or the Back Room (which is on the other side of the same building).

Grab some good whiskey based cocktail, grab some hot dogs and fries, and you're bound to enjoy your evening after work.

name: Handlebar Bar and Grill
formatted_address: 31 Polaris, Makati 1209, Metro Manila, Philippines

text.text:
Pricing was great, vodka tonic was so inexpensive compared to the rates in the other bars around this place. I only paid P150 per glass, I was so shocked when I saw the bill as I had a few glasses and was expecting a bigger amount on the check. Food was good enough, I had the fish & chips- chips could be bigger but not bad at all.

Only con is that the waitresses were not very friendly. They all weren't cheerful and welcoming despite the place not being packed with guests, so they couldn't have been tired.
A smile could make a huge difference. It's a sports bar, give us some energy. Lol
I was planning to play pool with them as I went alone that night- it was either a weekday or sunday night, I don't remember exactly but because they didn't seem approachable, I just decided not to.
One or a couple of them tho, were of course, nicer to the foreign guys on the other table who were quite loud btw, although I didn't mind it- I kind of expected that in a sports bar.

I hope management reads the reviews, because I am not the only one that said this here. I thought when I read the reviews before going there that the servers were probably just tired (I'd expect it on weekends) but it was quite slow when I went, and still.

text.text:
Following previous reviews about the friendliness of this place, I was very disappointed. I was not greeted, ignored several times when trying to catch the attention of the several waiting staff, and even worse, when paying the cashier, she just growled  "230" at me. I had to remind her of simple manners such as please and thank you.

In contrast, Cubano Cafe around the corner was a far better experience with a wonderful theme, atmosphere,  attentive and polite staff, great band and friendly clientele. I would recommend that over Handlebar!

text.text:
Service we got last night was incredibly top-notch! It was a friend's birthday and we were a large group of approx 13-20 guests (reservation done). We stayed until closing and orders kept on going until last call.  One staff (maybe the owner?) attended to us and it went perfectly well. Drinks and food came out timely, no errors nor missing orders, attentive and highly knowledgable of their products. Commendable skills! üëèüèΩBy far the best service I've ever experienced in the PH.

Drinks are creatively done and they definitely don't skimp on the alcohol content, not watered down. Food is also remarkable. Definitely get the one with the mushroom dip and the pizzas.

If youre driving, parking may be limited right out front but you can park on 14th Street close to the corner.
